<HEAD>Researchers Find Census Thought Destroyed by Stalin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet demographer was quoted as saying Wednesday that researchers have found the results of a 1937 census thought to have been destroyed by <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> to hide millions of deaths caused by his policies. Demographer <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolts </PERSON> said the census showed a population of 162 million, the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. The weekly magazine <ORGANIZATION> Ogonyok </ORGANIZATION>, in a story about the census published in December, said <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> claimed a population in 1937 of 170 million even though statistics could not confirm it. <PERSON> Tolts </PERSON> did not say where the census results were found, and said it was too early to use its figures to estimate how many people died in the purges, collectivization of agriculture and forced industrialization <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> imposed in the 1930s. Current Soviet reference books put the population at 163 million for 1917, the year of the revolution that brought the <ORGANIZATION> Bolsheviks </ORGANIZATION> to power. The current population is 284 million. <PERSON> Ogonyok </PERSON> blamed many of the deaths on a famine forced upon rural residents by government grain requisitions, but <PERSON> Tolts </PERSON> said <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s repressive policies also apparently were to blame He said the population of the <LOCATION> Saratov </LOCATION> region on the <LOCATION> Volga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> southeast of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> declined by 20 percent between 1927 and 1937, and the population of the Kursk region south of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> declined by 14 percent in the same period. <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1934 that the Soviet population the previous year was 168 million, although census officials put the figure at 165.7 million and one scientist put it as low as 158 million.
