<HEAD>Three Men Arrested In Racial Beating Incident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, ``It's the ..., to UPDATE with Buckner's
injuries; ADDS 3 grafs with arrests, arraignment, bail set; note
language in 11th and 14th grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A black man walking home from his job at a fast-food restaurant was attacked early Wednesday by six white men who shouted racial slurs as they pummelled him with sticks and a baseball bat, police said. The victim, <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>, took refuge in a pizza parlor, where the owners defended him against the gang and were themselves later harassed and assaulted, according to police. Three whites were arrested, and police were seeking three others. <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>, 24, was treated for bruises at a hospital and released. He said the assault, which occurred on <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, reminded him of the attack by a dozen white youths on three blacks in the <LOCATION> Howard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> section of <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> in December 1986. In that highly publicized case, one of the black men died when he was hit by a car while trying to escape. Three white teens were convicted of manslaughter last December. `` It's the same incident, racial,'' said <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>, who was treated for contusions at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vincent </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. `` I was minding my own business. I just get jumped for no reason.'' A short time after the attack, officers arrested <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Dessoye </PERSON>, 19; <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, 18; and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kish </PERSON>, 20, all of <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. They were charged with second-degree assault, aggravated harassment, criminal possession of a deadly instrument and possession of a controlled substance, marijuana. <PERSON> Dessoye </PERSON> was also charged with driving while intoxicated. `` <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Beach </PERSON> was the first thing I thought of,'' said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamartina </PERSON>, one of the owners of the Cafe DiSicilia pizzeria, who aided <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>. `` It was n't right. This guy was doing nothing wrong.'' <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>, a cook at a Burger King restaurant, said he was walking home through a mostly white section of <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> at about 12:20 a.m. when a car slowed down and the occupants began harassing him. `` They were calling me racial names _ nigger, <PERSON> blackie </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON> said. The men left their car and began beating him on the arm with sticks and a baseball bat, chasing him down the street. When <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON> fled into the pizzeria, `` he was nervous; his arm was messed up,'' <PERSON> Lamartina </PERSON> said. `` He said he just got jumped by a carload of white guys.'' <PERSON> Lamartina </PERSON> gave <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON> some ice and offered to have a worker drive him home. The group of white men appeared in front of the store, but they left after <PERSON> Lamartina </PERSON> and an employee went outside to disperse them. At about 1:20 a.m., after <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON> had been taken home, the group reappeared in front of the pizza parlor and taunted <PERSON> LaMartina </PERSON> and the store's other owner, <PERSON> Sal </PERSON> <PERSON> Taormina </PERSON>, calling them `` nigger lovers,'' <PERSON> LaMartina </PERSON> said. Both owners are white. `` One of them had a bat, and went to swing it at me, but <PERSON> Sal </PERSON> caught it,'' <PERSON> Lamartina </PERSON> recounted. `` We smacked them around a little bit, and they ran away.'' Neighbors who had witnessed the altercation called police, as did <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON> when he got home. A short time later, officers pulled over a red car and arrested <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Dessoye </PERSON>, 19, <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, 18, and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kish </PERSON>, 20, all of <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. They were identified by <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>, <PERSON> LaMartina </PERSON> and <PERSON> Taormina </PERSON> as the assailants. The three men were charged with second-degree assault, aggravated harassment, criminal possession of a deadly instrument and criminal possession of a controlled substance, marijuana. <PERSON> Dessoye </PERSON> was also charged with driving while intoxicated. All three pleaded innocent to the charges before Criminal Court Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>. Bail was set for Dessoye at $ 5,275 and $ 2,500 for both <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Kish </LOCATION>.
