<HEAD>A Star Rises from `Dust'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new film talent has emerged from the satirical movie `` A Handful of Dust.'' Her name is <PERSON> Kristin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>. The movie features <PERSON> Alec </PERSON> <PERSON> Guinness </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anjelica </PERSON> <PERSON> Huston </PERSON> in small but telling cameos, but it is dominated by <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> as the elegant English rose, <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Last </PERSON>, who drifts into a destructive affair with the young roue <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Beaver </PERSON> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Rupert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graves </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-. Based on <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Waugh </PERSON>'s savage 1934 novel, the $ 6 million film co-stars <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilby </PERSON> -LRB- Graves' co-star last year in `` Maurice'' -RRB- as <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON>'s hapless husband, <PERSON> Tony </PERSON>. It opens in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on June 24. `` I'm very pleased, I'm afraid, about the reaction that I'm getting It's so nice to have one's work appreciated,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said in an interview about her repeated raves from the British press. While reviews were mixed for the movie as a whole, critics hailed its female lead with the kind of accolades that banish anonymity forever. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> in The Standard called the actress `` the film's great find,'' adding, `` It will be criminal if British cinema does n't ... make a great star of her. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery-Massingberd </PERSON> in The <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> in The Guardian both called her `` a revelation.'' <PERSON> Iain </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnstone </PERSON> in The Sunday Times found the Paris-based actress `` a singular sensation'' in a movie that has returned her in triumph to the country she left eight years ago. `` I never really thought I'd be able to work in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, so ` A Handful of Dust' was an enormous pleasure and a great privilege,'' said the 28-year-old actress, who dropped out of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Speech </ORGANIZATION> and Drama after a year to move to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. `` I was doing a teacher training course and hated it, wanted to change and could n't,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, occasionally interrupting the interview to tend to the cries of her month-old daughter, <PERSON> Hannah </PERSON>. `` I was told I'd never be an actress anyway, and would never be able to play for real,'' she said. `` I thought it would be better to be totally miserable somewhere else and learn French at the same time.'' In <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, her life took a happier turn, beginning with her marriage to a French obstetrician. After drama training in French, she began getting parts in theater and in movies, and landed a role opposite the rock superstar Prince in his second movie, a bomb called `` Under the Cherry Moon.'' The film was not a financial success and was lampooned by critics. However, it enjoyed an international release. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Sturridge </PERSON>, the director of `` Handful of Dust'' and of the hit <PERSON> Waugh </PERSON> TV adaptation, `` Brideshead Revisited,'' saw it and cast <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> as <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON>. She had studied the book at school and said she seized the chance to become part of the film. `` I was sure it was going to be great,'' she recalled, before going back to the novel to immerse herself in Lady <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON>'s emotionally fatal attraction to the callow and cunning <PERSON> Beaver </PERSON> `` She likes taking someone who is absolutely dreadful and turning him into this fascinating young man whom no one can understand what she sees in him,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said, explaining the fascination on which the film's denouement depends: `` It makes her different, too.'' `` In the end, <PERSON> Beaver </PERSON> is much worse than <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> ever thought he was, really; by then she's in too deep,'' she said. The daughter of an affluent naval officer who died when she was five, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said she was bemused by the critique of the English class system that pervades the book and the film. `` It's quite sort of endearing, really, but it is ridiculous,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, a graduate of the posh <ORGANIZATION> Cheltenham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ladies </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> `` It's like some dear old piece of furniture that you like but you think is quite the most hideous thing in the world.'' She hopes not to be typecast as aristocratic English swells, and would like to do a French film next. `` I live there and I want to work there. You have to work hard, and I really mean to work hard,'' she said. `` I've got to make sure that the revelation does n't turn out to be a disaster.''
