<HEAD>Democratic Party Panel To Review Platform Draft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic platform writers, borrowing a page from congressional procedures, are putting a preliminary draft into a format that a party panel can mark up when it resumes deliberations Friday in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. The Democratic platform drafting committee, headed by Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, has already distributed a draft document to the campaigns of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> congressman serving as <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>'s chief link to the platform committee, said Wednesday, `` There will be a draft put before the members Friday morning.'' <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON> said the draft incorporates the dozen separate issue `` working papers'' produced at an earlier meeting of the platform writers on <LOCATION> Mackinac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION> `` It pulls them all together,'' he said. But <PERSON> Barnes </PERSON> said there has been no closing of the gap between the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> camps on whether the platform should embrace <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s call for higher taxes on the wealthy and a freeze on Pentagon spending. <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Platform </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the preliminary draft was still being finalized. She called it `` a collective effort'' by the same people who hammered out the earlier issue papers. The party released two final working papers on national security and political empowerment. The former reflects the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign's insistence that the platform call for `` stable'' defense budgets; the latter, in a nod to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, commits the party to removing `` impediments to the one-person, one-vote principle.'' Whatever emerges Friday from <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>'s 16-member drafting committee will be subject to further discussion and revision when the full 186-member <ORGANIZATION> Platform </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meets over the weekend in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> for the first time. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has enough delegates to force a floor fight at next month's <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> over any platform issue he chooses. Some <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> backers have hinted they would welcome a chance to shoot down a plank promising a tax hike. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, the 1984 nominee, got nothing but grief from his promise to raise taxes. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, has had his staff put the draft in mark-up format, with numbered lines, to make it easier for the drafting committee to make additions and deletions. Although a <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporter, <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> has been handling his drafting role in an impartial fashion. The 16 members include six each from the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> camps and four appointed by <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the party chairman, who has asked the platform writers to produce a short, visionary statement, free of special interest boilerplates. The new working paper on national security says the nation's strength has been `` sapped by a defense establishment that has wasted money on duplicative and dubious new weapons instead of investing more in readiness and mobility. `` We further believe that our strength is enhanced by stable defense budgets and by a commitment by our allies to assure their fair share of the costs and responsibilities required to maintain peace and liberty,'' the paper says. It says the Democrats `` will promote peace and prevent war _ not by trading weapons for hostages, not by sending brave Americans to undefined missions in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> ... not by toasting a tyrant like <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> as a disciple of democracy, but by maintaining a stable nuclear deterrent sufficient to counter any <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> threat, in standing up to any <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> adversary whenever necessary and sitting down with him whenever possible.'' The document calls for `` maintaining the special relationship with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' while promoting a <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> agreement that hews to the Camp David Accords. It says a Democratic administration would `` end all vestiges of the failed policy of constructive engagement and will declare <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> a terrorist state -LRB- and -RRB- impose comprehensive sanctions.'' The paper would commit the party to same-day voter registration and registration by mail and calls for a removal of `` impedidents to the one-person, one-vote principle,'' it said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who won 29 percent of the primary votes but just 24 percent of the delegates, has complained about the way some states allocated delegates.
