<FIRST>r w PM-Iran-Contra     06-23 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Classified Documents Ruling Indicates Fall Trial for North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The judge in the Iran-Contra conspiracy case is setting up procedures for dealing with classified documents in an apparent effort to bring fired <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> to trial by fall. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> ordered North to identify by July 11 which secret government documents the retired <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> lieutenant colonel wants to disclose in court to rebut charges that he illegally diverted Iranian arms-sale profits to the Nicaraguan rebels. In a ruling on Wednesday, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said that both the public and prosecutors would be barred from a July 14 hearing to determine if any of the documents are relevant to the case against <PERSON> North </PERSON>. The judge also rejected a defense motion to declare the Classified Information Procedures Act unconstitutional as it applied to the case of North, former national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> and arms dealers <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>. The four defendants, whom <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> has said must be tried separately, contended that the law unfairly required them to tell the prosecution what documents they intended to make public before the trials. Such disclosures would give independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> an unfair tactical advantage, the defense said. Acknowledging the problem, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said `` strict application of the statute to this proceeding would not only be difficult, but impossible to accomplish consistent with a fair and expeditious resolution of this case.'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> noted that the large volume of classified documents collected by <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s investigation about 200,000 pages by the latest count _ posed unique problems for a trial judge that were probably not envisioned when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed the classified information statute in 1980. `` Some of the witnesses and defendants, particularly <PERSON> North </PERSON>, operated from secure locations in the White House with full access to the most sensitive information and most critical national security intelligence methods and sources available to the government,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said. `` This information, and even some methods and sources, are inextricably enmeshed in the events challenged by the indictment,'' he added. But in enacting the law, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> gave trial judges authority `` to fashion creative and fair solutions'' to difficult problems posed by such sensitive information, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said. Lawmakers `` emphasized that the court should not undertake to balance the national security interests of the government against the rights of the defendant but rather that in the end remedies and sanctions against the government must be designed to make the defendant whole again.'' `` While afforded this leeway, the court is unable to determine definitively at this stage whether or not the classified document problems presented by this case can be resolved,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said in the 16-page opinion. `` It proposes to make the effort, but the complexity of the situation defies obvious answers. Final ruling on the -LRB- defense -RRB- motion must await further developments.'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said that he would exclude <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> from discussions of whether classified documents that <PERSON> North </PERSON> proposes to disclose are relevant to the case. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> will decide which documents are relevant and admissible as evidence. Only after an interdepartmental task force has identified relevant documents that pose national security problems will <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> be included in the process of how to present them in court, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said. Indicating a desire to move the case to trial, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> gave the government secrecy experts until Aug. 1 to complete their review of the documents identified by North. The task force, composed of representatives of various government intelligence agencies, is reviewing the documents that <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> collected during his investigation from the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. After the panel's task is completed, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said he would convene closed hearings to determine how to edit out portions of documents that can not be declassified. Under the law, the court has the power to order deletions of sensitive material or to substitute a statement of facts that the document would prove if it were shown to the jury. If a sufficient number of documents can not be disclosed in any fashion, the court can dismiss charges against a defendant on the ground he could not get a fair trial. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>'s ruling follows his determination last week that <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s investigation was not tainted by impermissible use of the testimony that <PERSON> North </PERSON>, <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> gave to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year under limited grants of immunity from prosecution Both decisions indicate that <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> has determined that, barring unforeseen problems created by classified documents, the case can move ahead to trial by September. In a statement, <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said: `` We appreciate the court's prompt ruling on the constitutionality of the Classified Information Procedures Act as it applies to this case and we are prepared to move forward as directed by the court.''
