<HEAD>Panel Wants Two Special Tax Breaks Back in Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House tax-writers want to renew two targeted benefits of the type that were supposed to be wiped out when the tax law was overhauled in 1986. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> agreed Wednesday to renew for three years a tax benefit for employees who receive educational assistance from their bosses, and to extend for one year a special credit for owners of low-income rental housing. The panel, working on a package of miscellaneous tax items proposed by Chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., is considering extension of a third special benefit: tax-exempt mortgage bonds used to help low-income people buying their first home That exemption is a favorite of state and local government officials, who administer the mortgage assistance. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the auditing arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, says the program `` does little to increase home ownership opportunities.'' About $ 50 billion of such bonds were issued between 1982 and 1986, at a cost to the federal government of about $ 7.5 billion, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> estimated. About two-thirds of the homebuyers who benefited could have bought their homes without assistance, the agency said. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wiped out several such special-interest benefits when it revised the tax law two years ago, contending that the tax system should not be used to provide subsidies when federal appropriations could do the job better. But several still remain. The committee hopes to complete work next week on this year's tax bill, which is designed mainly to correct hundreds of errors that found their way into the 1986 law The `` technical corrections'' bill is being used as the vehicle for a few substantive tax amendments, including those proposed by <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>. The committee, meeting behind closed doors, voted Wednesday to: _ Tighten and renew through 1990 an expired law under which employees could avoid tax on up to $ 5,250 a year worth of educational assistance provided by their employers The benefit was designed to help lower-income workers prepare for better jobs. Under the new version, the exclusion would be reduced as income rises above a level that is yet to be determined, and upper-income workers would receive no benefit. No benefit would be available for post-graduate work. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration opposes renewal of the exclusion, which would cost the government about $ 540 million. _ Extend for one year the credit for owners of low-income rental housing, which is due to expire at the end of 1989 This would cost $ 543 million. _ Write into law an <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> decision that sick pay, accumulated vacation leave and similar compensation received by employees of state and local governments and non-profit organizations should not be taxed when earned _ Exempt from Social Security taxes the wages of members of Amish and other religious sects that have religious objections to such programs Committee aides estimated this would affect about 10,000 workers; about 750 self-employed people _ most of them <LOCATION> Amish </LOCATION> _ already are exempt. _ Deny Social Security benefits to any person who in the future is ordered deported as a Nazi war criminal _ Exempt from taxation a $ 10-million trust fund created in 1985 to finance rehabilitation of <LOCATION> Enjebi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Enewetak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atoll </ORGANIZATION>, which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> used as a target for testing nuclear weapons in the 1940s and 1950s A similar exemption was voted in 1982 for the benefit of <LOCATION> Bikini </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. The biggest portion of the tax increase required to pay for the benefits in the bill would come from corporations that own shares of other corporations and from owners of single-premium life insurance.
