<HEAD>House Panel Approves Drug and Alcohol Testing For Rail Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislation requiring the nation's railroad workers to undergo random drug testing has begun to make progress in the election-year conscious House. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> transportation, tourism and hazardous materials subcommittee voted 13-0 on Wednesday to send the measure to the full Energy and <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The committee's chairman, Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., who has been reluctant to support the measure, is now expected to give the legislation prompt consideration `` I expect it to be called up right away,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Luken </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, the subcommittee chairman, after his panel approved the bill. <PERSON> Luken </PERSON> co-sponsored the measure with Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, the subcommittee's ranking Republican, who said public support for ridding drug and alcohol abuse from the transportation industry is `` simply overwhelming.'' There has been growing support in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for drug testing legislation since Jan. 4, 1987, when an <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> passenger train and three <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> locomotives collided in Chase, Md. The crash killed 16 people and injured 175 others, and two <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> crewmen have admitted to having smoked marijuana shortly before the disaster. Railroad labor officials have opposed proposals for random testing, saying that the procedures would violate the privacy of the workers and unfairly threaten their careers because of the risk of inaccurate laboratory analysis. That opposition has been diminishing, however, as election-year pressures have increased for lawmakers to do something about drug abuse. In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> proposed drug testing rules for railroad workers on May 5 that many union leaders consider harsher than the legislation. The bill would require not only random testing, which supporters say would deter alcohol and drug abuse, but testing after accidents, before hiring, for reasonable cause and as a part of annual physical examinations. Workers who test positive would be given a second, more sophisticated test to confirm the results. If they test positive again, they would be suspended without pay and required to complete rehabilitation programs to keep their jobs. Employees who refuse to take tests would risk being fired. Procedures would be established to certify the laboratories being used and to protect workers against harassment. <PERSON> Luken </PERSON>, who had long expressed fears about erroneous test results, resisted introducing legislation until June 3. That was five weeks after Dr. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hunt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, whose daughter <LOCATION> Ceres </LOCATION>, 16, was killed in the Chase crash, visited newspapers and television and radio stations in <PERSON> Luken </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> district to argue that random testing was needed. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has already approved legislation that would require random drug and alcohol testing for railroad, airline and trucking industry workers. Rail workers involved in accidents are already subject to drug and alcohol tests, but those rules are being challenged in court.
