<HEAD>EPA Asks 10 States To Develop Aldicarb Management Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Under a new proposal, 10 states in the upper <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and Southeast are going to have to tell the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> how they will protect ground water from contamination with the highly toxic pesticide aldicarb. In its first action under a draft strategy aimed at protecting ground water from pesticides, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that it was considering an alternative that would require `` pesticide management plans'' from as many as 24 states. Only the 10 states in the main proposal, chosen on the basis of their crops and the general vulnerability of ground water, were identified: <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. In the first five, aldicarb has not been found in ground water; in the second five, it has been found in concentrations above 10 parts per billion, which is the amount the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> considers safe. Ground water, which supplies drinking water to half the nation's population, was once thought safe from pollution But evidence to the contrary has accumulated in recent years. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has found 63 pesticides in ground water. The agency reported that one-third of about 35,000 ground water samples it tested contained some aldicarb. <ORGANIZATION> Aldicarb </ORGANIZATION>, sold under the trade name Temik by <ORGANIZATION> Rhone-Poulenc </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ag </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Triangle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, is used on potatoes, citrus, peanuts, cotton and other crops to protect them against scores of insects, root worms and mites. As much as 5.7 million pounds of the pesticide are used each year. Its use already is restricted, and it is banned in a few areas like <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, where 3,100 homes must use expensive charcoal filtration to remove it from their well water. In humans, aldicarb can interfere with the transmission of nerve impulses. High concentrations can cause digestive upset, dehydration, blurred vision, disorientation, seizures, unconsciousness and death. More than 1,000 poisonings and two stillbirths were reported in Western states and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> in 1985 from California-grown watermelons contaminated with aldicarb. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has been studying the pesticide for four years, and still is investigating how much might be in typical diets. The manufacturer said Wednesday its latest survey showed `` residues were rarely present.'' The agency's draft strategy leaves many key decisions to the states, like banning aldicarb's use in certain areas and limiting frequency of application. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, assistant <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator for pesticides, told reporters Wednesday that the agency probably would ban use of aldicarb in states that refuse to submit plans. States might win <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> approval to permit contamination of ground water that would n't be used for drinking water, he said, as long as residents of the state have had a chance to comment on the plan. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> also is proposing to ban aldicarb use within 300 feet of any well and to require state training programs for applicators to teach about ground water effects. <ORGANIZATION> Rhone-Poulenc </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal reflects `` sound principles for drinking water protection,'' and said it would cooperate. A company spokesman, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmotzer </PERSON>, said, `` We are going to manage this product even more stringently than required, as we are doing in some instances now.'' In some counties in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, he said, the company requires 1,000-foot well protection zones. Elsewhere, though, 50 feet might suffice, and <ORGANIZATION> Rhone-Poulenc </ORGANIZATION> might seek a variable zone in comments to the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Schmotzer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldman </PERSON>, coordinator of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Misuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pesticides </ORGANIZATION>, criticized the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> for not considering non-chemical strategies, such as crop rotations, in calculating the costs and benefits of aldicarb use. In addition to the five states from which <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> wants management plans, aldicarb also has been found in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virgina </LOCATION> in concentrations above 10 ppb, and in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in concentrations below that. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s proposal also would require <ORGANIZATION> Rhone-Poulenc </ORGANIZATION> to monitor ground water the agency considers highly vulnerable in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>.
