<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> says he's afraid there will be a dangerous overreaction by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the public to disclosures of a massive <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> fraud and bribery investigation. `` You do n't close a bank because there's been a bank robbery,'' <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> said in an interview Wednesday. `` And you do n't conclude that we do n't need a strong defense because of the actions of some faithless employees. It's important to bear in mind that the needs of defense have n't changed at all as a result of these stories.'' <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> also said that he had no apologies to make for his management style while serving as secretary of defense. He said he did n't know about the federal investigation until it was revealed last week. Nor, he said, did he have any suspicions of wrongdoing before he left office last November. `` I think the -LRB- contract -RRB- procedures in effect are proper,'' the former defense chief and presidential confidant said. `` We needed to regain military strength quickly and we did. But I did n't exercise any hands-off management technique. I had briefings regularly, once a week or every two weeks, on the major weapons programs. `` But no matter how careful you are, you're not going to be able to eliminate dishonesty.'' <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> served almost seven years as secretary of defense before stepping down because of the ill health of his wife. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, the ongoing fraud and bribery probe began during his tenure and involved, at least to some extent, contracting actions that occurred before his departure. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials say the inquiry centers on allegations that <ORGANIZATION>