<HEAD>Train Derailment Ignites Fire In Ky.; 2,500 Evacuated; Flights
Banned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf and ADD one graf to UPDATE with comment from
CSX CORRECTING that 36 cars of 121-car train derailed, sted 32-car
train derailed; include route of train.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CROFTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thirty-six cars of train derailed and one car filled with phosphorus burst into flames Wednesday night, forcing 2,500 people to evacuate and bans on flights over four counties, officials said. No injuries were reported, said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, spokesman for the state Disaster and <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Frankfort </LOCATION>. He said a phosphorus fire can not be quenched and must burn itself out. Smoke from the fire could explode when temperatures reach 90 degrees, he said. `` You're talking about big, big, big trouble,'' <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> said. `` Water makes it burn hotter.'' The evacuation was ordered for residents of <LOCATION> Nortonville </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> and <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> downwind to the east of the burning car, which derailed in <LOCATION> Christian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> Hopkin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> line. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> early Thursday restricted all air travel over those counties and over <ORGANIZATION> Muhlenberg </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> McLean </LOCATION> counties. Two highways also were closed, officials said. The <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> train derailed at 7:55 p.m., 3 -LCB- miles north of <LOCATION> Crofton </LOCATION>, a community of 800 in western <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, state police said. <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> said smoke from the fire could be seen up to 30 miles away. No one in <LOCATION> Crofton </LOCATION>, population 800, was evacuated, said Novi Mainire of the <LOCATION> Crofton </LOCATION> police department. Officials were unable to determine if other chemicals were being transported on the train, but <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> said only one car was on fire. <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ripley </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON> said the 36 cars that derailed were roughly in the middle of the 121-car train, which was traveling from <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>.
