d for lifting sections of other politicians' speeches without attribution. A videotape, juxtaposing a <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> campaign speech with a speech by British politician <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON> and showing striking similarities between the two, was sent to various news organizations. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said he had credited <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON> on other occasions, but had neglected to do so that time. It was later revealed that <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' campaign manager, distributed the video. One day after news reports linked the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign to the video, the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor admitted that <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> was the source of the video. <PERSON> Sasso </PERSON> resigned from the campaign, as did <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Tully </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' campaign issues director. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, 45, is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. He was released from the hospital last month after successful surgery to correct an aneurysm near his brain. It was the second aneurysm he had suffered since February. An aneurysm is a ballooning of the weakened wall of an artery and is caused by disease or injury.
