<TEXT>
 Consultants hired by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> have concluded that to tear down a portion of the new <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> chancery in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> would be an `` engineering nightmare,'' according to a report published today. Members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and intelligence officers disclosed last year that the unfinished building was riddled with Soviet listening devices. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> asked a team of engineers, architects and security experts to study the structure and analyze solutions for making it secure. The consultants, in their initial finding, have concluded that `` partial deconstruction'' of the eight-story building `` is n't feasible'' and would be more dangerous and difficult than demolishing the entire the structure and rebuilding, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported today One of the consultants referred to `` an engineering nightmare,'' the Times said. The new chancery was to have been the main embassy building for diplomatic and classified activities. But after $ 22 million was spent on it, construction was stopped in 1985. A <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> source told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the department has received a portion of the consultants' report, but the complete report is not due until August. The source said no decision on what to do about the building has been made. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamb </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for diplomatic security, told the Times, `` The building experts are saying that a partial deconstruction is n'