RSON> Katz </PERSON> agreed that the subscription service could eliminate billing disputes. `` There's no excuse for somebody to say they did n't know what they were getting,'' he said. `` They signed up.'' But <LOCATION> Golan </LOCATION> contended that the adult-oriented business will suffer because people wo n't want to be identified as a subscriber to 915. `` It's a very touchy issue, and it's being approached in a very negative way,'' he said. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Mid-Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audiotex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the group is considering legal action to block the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s decision. The commission is using the 915 service to drive dial-a-porn lines from the marketplace, <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said, adding, `` What they're doing is doing indirectly what they ca n't do directly. Annual revenue from 976-type services is about $ 330 million nationwide, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bulletin </ORGANIZATION>, an industry newsletter. Of that, about $ 54 million is from `` dial-a-porn'' lines; $ 90 million from conference conversation lines; and $ 186 million from general-interest lines, such as recorded sports results.
