<HEAD>Congressional Conferees Scale Back Military Role in Drug Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional negotiators working on a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget bill have scaled back plans for a major military role in the anti-drug effort and have cut President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s request for Star Wars spending, sources said The <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee has approved all but a few details of a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1, and expect to complete their work later this week, the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. An agreement will send the huge bill back to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floors for approval, and it will then go to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> for his signature. The bill authorizes $ 299.5 billion in defense spending for the upcoming fiscal year, down slightly from the $ 300 billion the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> is allowed to spend in the current year. The sources said Wednesday that the conference committee agreed to increase spending for an anti-drug program in which <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officers ride aboard <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> warships patrolling in offshore waters. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officers have civilian arrest powers that they can use if the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> vessels encounter suspected drug-trafficking boats. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> has about 300 people assigned to the program, riding aboard <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships in teams of five to seven people per vessel. Another 100 <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> personnel will be added to the program in the next three months, the sources said. The House had voted overwhelmingly to order <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to have the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> essentially seal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> borders against illegal drug shipments. Later, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> easily voted to give <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officers civilian arrest powers if warships stopped suspected drug trafficking vessels in international waters. But the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> strongly opposed both those provisions. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said the military should n't get involved in civilian law enforcement and warned that even if it did, illegal drugs still would flow into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The final compromise, while dropping the more far-reaching anti-drug provisions passed by each chamber, requires the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> to increase the help it provides to civilian anti-drug agencies in spotting and tracking planes and ships that might be carrying contraband. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> already provide intelligence help from radar planes and ships, and <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said he has no opposition to increasing that aid. The conference committee, meanwhile, agreed to authorize $ 4.1 billion for <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION>, formally known as the Strategic Defense Initiative, the sources said. That is up from the current $ 3.9 billion budget, but far below the $ 4.8 billion <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had sought. In addition, the conferees dropped an amendment approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> that would have required a halt in all but the smallest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear weapons tests. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> had rejected the proposed ban. The legislators also agreed to authorize $ 250 million each for the Midgetman and MX programs, a pair of controversial efforts to develop new land-based atomic-tipped weapons. Another $ 250 million was approved for spending after a new president is elected Nov. 8, the sources said.
