<HEAD>Nevada Reservoir is Drying Up for the First Time Ever</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Drought-Heat Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For nearly three-quarters of a century, <LOCATION> Lahontan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reservoir </LOCATION> has made an agricultural oasis of this desert region, weathering good years and bad to irrigate 65,000 acres of alfalfa and other crops. But after two consecutive winters that produced half the normal precipitation in western <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lahontan </LOCATION> is drying up for the first time since its completion in 1915. Like many areas in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and Plains straining under one of the worst droughts in 50 years, this fertile area will soon be out of water. Some fields will lack irrigation in a few weeks and by mid-September, the 600-mile network of canals will be dry, officials said Wednesday. `` We've got everybody on a 70 percent allocation but it's going to be pretty tough to meet that,'' <PERSON> Lyman </PERSON> <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON>, project manager of the Truckee-Carson Irrigation District said. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> DeBraga </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Fallon </PERSON> farmer and president of the irrigation district, said even the 30 percent cutback `` equates to dollars when you start losing tonnage on the alfalfa.'' When the flow to the alfalfa taps out, `` we'll just try to keep it alive in hopes next year will be a better year,'' he said. `` It is n't a rosy picture.'' The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevada-Reno </ORGANIZATION> has estimated the drought could put a $ 14 million dent in the state's agriculture industry, the No. 3 business behind gaming and mining. Alfalfa, a legume with small, purplish flowers that is the region's principal cash crop, is mainly a pasture plant used for hay, which has fallen into short supply throughout the farm belt because of the drought. <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON> said Lahontan currently holds 121,550 acre-feet of water, barely one-third its capacity of 314,000 acre-feet. When it reaches 10,000 acre-feet, or 32.6 million gallons of water, the gates will be closed to maintain a small reserve for next year. An acre-foot is the amount of water that covers one acre to a depth of one foot. The reservoir, which meanders for 20 miles along the former <LOCATION> Carson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> bed 35 miles east of <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>, is also a popular destination for fishing, swimming and boating. The project was begun shortly after the turn of the century and within a decade had transformed the desert area into an agricultural oasis. Despite close calls in 1924, 1929 and 1931, the reservoir never has failed the farmers and ranchers it serves. Lahontan is fed by the <LOCATION> Carson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which is nearly exhausted, and by water diverted from the <LOCATION> Truckee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> flowing from <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION> and other smaller upstream reserves. While farmers have made their first cutting of alfalfa, most will at best get only one more cutting rather than the typical three, said <PERSON> Jeanni </PERSON> <PERSON> Conlan </PERSON>, of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stabilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Fallon </PERSON>. Those who have made four cuttings in the past are n't likely to be that lucky this summer, she added. `` I'd guess there will be little water left to raise a fourth crop of hay,'' she said. Most farmers make their third harvest between mid-September and mid-October, about the time the water is expected to run out, Ms. <PERSON> Conlan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> DeBraga </PERSON> said he had not heard of any farmers or ranchers being in danger of foreclosure, `` but that's always a possibility, even in a 100 percent irrigation year.'' `` In years like this, it's that much closer,'' he said. `` Next year's the tough one. With all the reservoirs being empty like they're going to be this fall, it would take an excellent year to get back even close to normal.''
