<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar closed substantially higher today against the Japanese yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, while share prices declined for the fourth consecutive trading day. The dollar closed at 128.55 yen, up a strong 0.95 yen from Wednesday's finish. It had opened the day, however, up more than two yen at 129.80, the currency's highest level in nearly four months, and briefly touched a low of 128.25. Traders attributed the dollar's decline after an initial surge to profit taking by institutional investors. `` Investors who had purchased the dollar earlier decided to collect profits on the higher dollar,'' said a foreign exchange dealer with a major <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> commercial bank, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Trading became quiet in the afternoon as dealers, concerned the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> would step into the market to stem the further rise of the dollar, stepped aside, he said. The <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s central bank does not officially comment on its market activity. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, a 64.79-point loser Wednesday, lost another 127.85 points, or 0.46 percent, to finish the day's session at 27,732.93. `` A wait-and-see attitude among investors coupled with profit-taking share selling pulled the Nikkei index back,'' said a stock analyst with a major securities house, who also demanded anonymity. Encouraged by the strong dollar and overnight advance on Wall Street, the Nikkei Index, the stock market's key barometer, rose to a high of around 28,008 points, up about 147 points at one time during the morning trading, dealers said. The brokerage official said that except for certain large-capitals, most issues were either finished lower or remained unchanged as investors became worried about inflation and higher interest rates in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The strong dollar caused Japanese government bond prices to fall, driving up yields and concern about domestic interest rates, traders said. Volume on the first section was estimated at 1 billion shares, down from 1.2 billion shares Wednesday. Losers include chemicals, automobiles and financials. Some of the large-capital steels and machineries finished higher.
