<SECOND>PM-Fossil Find,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Continent's Oldest Well-Preserved Fossils of Land Vertebrates
Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists today reported finding <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s oldest well-preserved fossils of land-dwelling vertebrates, and said the find should yield important information about early species of such animals. Several hundred fossils have been collected in southeast <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> from what was apparently a pond when the animals lived 335 million years ago, scientists said in today's issue of the British journal Nature. News of the fossils had been publicized in 1986. The Nature report was written by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolt </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Field </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> History </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Witzke </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resouces </ORGANIZATION>, and M.P. <ORGANIZATION> McAdams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> William </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oskaloosa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. The ancient animals lived 15 million years after amphibians appeared on the scene. The fossils include nearly complete skeletons of at least two apparently new species of amphibians, including one related to ancient animals called anthracosaurs, researchers said. At least eight fish species are also represented, they said. The find is important, partly because it is the first such site of the Mississippian age reported from the middle of the continent, <PERSON> Alec </PERSON> <PERSON> Panchen </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newcastle </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> wrote in an editorial accompanying the report. Earlier, similar animals of the Mississippian age had been known mainly from <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION> and an area including northwern <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, he said.
