 The dollar rose in active European trading this morning, supported by widespread bullish sentiment. Gold prices were lower, depressed by the dollar's strength. Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was buoyed by the recent improvement in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit, higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates and indications that world monetary authorities are n't overly concerned about a stronger dollar. The dollar started the European day on a very bullish note in hectic trading dominated by buyers. The market then calmed down a bit, with more regular two-way trading. One Italian trader said central bank intervention against the dollar's rise had been minimal, effectively giving the market a green light to take the dollar higher. `` The dollar is on a forward march,'' a trader at a West German bank in <LOCATION> Dusseldorf </LOCATION> said. `` The mood is confident.'' But another dealer at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> said the dollar's near-term direction is n't yet clear `` The market is still unsure whether the trend will continue upwards or whether there will be some profit-taking,'' he said. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar rose 0.95 yen to a closing 128.55 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted higher at 128.93 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's rates: _ 1.7865 West German marks, up from 1.7740 _ 1.4802 Swiss francs, up from 1.4720 _ 6.0285 French francs, up from 5.9747 _ 2.0094 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9975 _ 1,325.25 Italian lire, up from 1,314.50 _ 1.2070 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2100 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the It cost $ 1.7648 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.7710 late Wednesday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 448.40 a troy ounce and at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a r