<HEAD>Can Rainmakers Help Drought-Stricken Areas?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists, medicine men and farmers have long sought ways to make it rain on command. While that day may be nearer, rainmaking can not yet offer hope for breaking the drought gripping <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Experiments have shown that cloud seeding `` can offer a modest increase in what precipitation does fall, but it would not break a drought or anything like that,'' said meteorologist <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poellot </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION>. Studies `` suggest man's ability to modify precipitation is really quite minor,'' added <PERSON> Roscoe </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Braham </PERSON>, who teaches meteorology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>. `` We're not dealing with a minor problem in the drought, we're dealing with a major catastrophe,'' <PERSON> Braham </PERSON> said `` There's no reason to think cloud seeding could do anything to ameliorate the dry conditions that we have.'' Even <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Atmospherics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, in <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, the nation's largest cloud-seeding company, conceded that `` weather modification, as a cure-all for drought situations, is probably not a very viable technology.'' <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Boe </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which operates a weather modification program in that state, held out hope that `` something can be done.'' But, he noted, `` in a drought, the opportunities are less.'' Seeding `` might shorten the length of a drought a bit, but you will not see a dramatic result from it in most cases.'' he said. Poellot reported that cloud-seeding experiments have increased rainfall by as much as 10 percent. But, he noted, `` for cloud seeding to work, it needs some clouds. So if there are no clouds, you're out of luck.'' That same thought was echoed by the other meteorologists. `` The atmosphere just does not have any clouds in it; we've been totally cloud free,'' <PERSON> Braham </PERSON> said. `` We've been in the field since June 1, but we've flown very litte,'' added <PERSON> Boe </PERSON>, whose agency operates an airborne cloud-seeding program covering 6.6 million acres of western <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> spends about $ 1.5 million per two-year budget cycle on weather modification, half from the state and half from a tax voted by residents of the counties affected. <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> said that the cost of running a commercial four-month summertime cloud-seeding program covering 3,000 to 5,000 acres in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> would typically run from $ 100,000 to $ 125,000. Making it rain has obsessed mankind for thousands of years, and many hoped for a breakthrough a few decades ago when the first successes were achieved. In 1946, <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaefer </PERSON> accomplished the goal, although he actually made it snow, rather than rain. Through the centuries, all sorts of less scientific methods had been attempted, including animal sacrifice, setting out pots of water, calling on various gods, clashing armor, ringing church bells and even firing artillery into the sky. <PERSON> Schaefer </PERSON>, in a famous Nov. 13, 1946, experiment near <LOCATION> Schenectady </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, sprinkled three pounds of ground dry ice into a cloud and within minutes snowflakes formed, and a hole appeared in the cloud. A lot of experimentation was done in the 1970s, sponsored by state and federal governments, but there has been relatively little scientific work on changing the weather in the 1980s. That is partly because of reductions in money available for the work and partly because `` the scientists succeeded in defining the situations where rainfall increases looked feasible and those where it did n't look so feasible, and the window of opportunity kept getting smaller and smaller,'' <PERSON> Braham </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Boe </PERSON> stressed that any cloud-seeding program has to be a continuing one. `` If you're going to start a weather modification program to deal with drought, and when it's over you bag the program, you're taking the wrong tack,'' he said Long-term cloud seeding adds to the deep ground moisture, and can help resist the damage of droughts.
</TEXT>
