<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 School systems comprised of inner-city neighborhoods and suburbs that bus students for racial balance are the most successful at maintaining integrated schools, a study concludes. The finding is one of several contained in a report released Wednesday at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` That was one of the more interesting findings, given the fierce battling that goes on over desegregation,'' said political scientist <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Orfield </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>. `` The perception is often that reassigning students to other neighborhoods encourages ` white flight.''' `` But the places that have been most successful _ <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, most every big city in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> except <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> _ have been those where the city and suburbs are in the same district and you can implement a districtwide desegregation plan,'' <PERSON> Orfield </PERSON> said. Researchers, led by <PERSON> Orfield </PERSON> and political scientist <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Monfort </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION>, analyzed data from the 60 largest public school systems between 1967 and 1986. They concluded the schools have become increasingly segregated over that period because of a dramatic rise in Hispanic students and a steady erosion in white enrollment. `` Predictions about central city districts losing the majority of their white students came true,'' <PERSON> Orfield </PERSON> said Wednesday, `` but now, not only are blacks still being segregated, Hispanics are being more segregated at an even-faster rate. `` However, the segregation is not the result of whites leaving public schools, so much as migration patterns and changes in the birth rates,'' he added. Among the report's most significant findings: _ Total enrollment declined by 15 percent in the 60 districts to 6.7 million over the 19-year period White enrollment declined by 16 percent, while the number of black students increased by 5 percent and Hispanic students by 103 percent. _ The 25 largest central city school districts now serve 28 percent of all black students, 30 percent of all Hispanics, but only 3 percent of white students `` What that means,'' he said, `` is that the school systems that are decisive to the future of large parts of our minority groups are almost irrelevant to the white population.'' _ Almost half of the largest public school districts are now in the suburbs and metropolitan counties alongside urban centers The researchers did not attempt to assess the consequences of segregation or to propose solutions. But <PERSON> Orfield </PERSON> said: `` Schools that serve black and Hispanic populations exclusively serve a disproportionate number of poor kids. They continue to do much worse than white schools in academic achievement, graduation rates, and almost any other measure of providing a successful education. `` And the worst part,'' he added, `` is that almost nothing substantial is being done to change it.''
</TEXT>
