<HEAD>Drought May Help Some As Great Lakes Water Levels Decline</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `If the ...,' with 1 graf to delete incorrecT
definition of mean. SUBS 6th graf, ``Our docks ...,' to correct
spelling of `municipal.'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two years ago, high water levels sent waves crashing over miles of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> shoreline, chewing up beaches, submerging marinas and causing millions of dollars in destruction. Today, drought has helped lake water levels drop up to 3 feet since then _ good news for the suffering recreation industry and for home owners who feared their property was doomed. `` The drought is having a major effect on lake levels,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON>, head of lake hydrology at the <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lakes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mich </LOCATION>. If the trend continues, the lakes will drop below their monthly average levels for the first time in 10 to 15 years. Declining water levels have decreased the threat of erosion and landslides and improved conditions for sunbathers and recreational boaters, said <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON>, whose lab is operated by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` Our docks are 4 or 5 feet above water level,'' said <PERSON> Patty </PERSON> <PERSON> Demink </PERSON>, who works at South Haven Municipal Marina. `` When I first started coming here -LRB- two years ago -RRB-, if it rained the water would go over the docks.'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>, 71, said that in 1986, he and his wife feared their `` dream house,'' which sits 280 feet above <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, might slip into the lake. `` About 50 feet of our frontage was destroyed in two landslides,'' <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON> said. `` Now, we feel more confident that we'll be able to stay here longer.'' The Great Lakes have dropped 2 feet to 3 feet since their record-highs in 1986, when waves left lakefront homes teetering on scooped-out bluffs. On June 17, <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> was 31 inches lower than it was in October 1986, <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON> said. In the last month, lakes <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Huron </PERSON> dropped 2 inches, <PERSON> Erie </PERSON> dropped 3 inches, Superior stayed the same and <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> went up an inch, he said. Lakes <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Erie </PERSON> peaked in the first half of April and have been steady or falling since, <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON> said. In an average year, the lakes do not peak until July or August, but hot, dry weather has caused much water to evaporate, <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON> said. Even if the drought ends, most of the moisture from much-needed rain would be absorbed by the parched soil and little would run into the Great Lakes. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> has considered diverting some water from <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rivers </ORGANIZATION>, which have been drying up in the drought. `` Changing the diversions would only change the lake levels by a matter of a couple of inches,'' <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON> said. A 1929 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling in a lawsuit, however, set limits on how much water could be diverted from the lake into the river system. The lawsuit was brought against <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> by other Great Lakes states and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Fredenburg </PERSON>, a spokesman for the North Central Division of the corps of engineers. Since then, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> must be petitioned to change the limit. The latest came in 1980 when the court said 3,200 cubic feet per second could be diverted. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Wente </PERSON>, executive director of <LOCATION> Wilmette </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, north of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said although he is glad the water has dropped from levels that swamped his marina two years ago, the shrinking trend has drawbacks. `` We're a good 3 or 4 inches from where we were a month ago,'' he said. `` We've had to do a lot more dredging here in the harbor entrance, and it's costing us more.'' `` If it continues at this rate, it's going to be trouble in a couple of years,'' he said.
