<HEAD>^Ceremonies Commemorating Berlin Airlift Open Today</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with today's reenactment, other
details. Pick up 8th graf: `The Berlin...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A vintage <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> transport plane left <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> today to mark the 40th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Airlift, a massive mission to feed and clothe millions of Berliners sealed off from the rest of the world by Russian troops. The C-47 aircraft took off from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and landed at <LOCATION> Templehof </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> at 4:14 p.m. at -LRB- 10:14 a.m. EDT -RRB-. It's a short flight between the two cities, but for the 2 million Berliners blockaded by the Soviets at the end of World War II, the 250-mile jaunt meant the difference between life and death. During the airlift's 15 months, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British cargo planes ferried more than 1.8 million tons of food, coal and other vital supplies to the Allied-controlled sectors of <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, an enclave deep inside what was then Soviet-held territory and is now <LOCATION> Communist </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Among the passengers aboard the C-47 flying to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> today were the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, British and French ambassadors to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Earlier, the ambassadors attended the opening of an airlift exhibit in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> and ceremonies at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rhine Main Air Base near <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. Most of the airlift flights originated at Rhine Main. Taking part were <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burt </PERSON>, British Ambassador Sir <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallaby </PERSON>, French Ambassador <PERSON> Serge </PERSON> <PERSON> Boidevaix </PERSON>, West German Defense Minister <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Scholz </PERSON>, and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Eberhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Diepgen </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airlift </LOCATION> began June 26, 1948 and ended Sept. 30, 1949. It was masterminded by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> Gen. <PERSON> Lucius </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clay </PERSON>, the military governor of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> zone of conquered <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> following World War II. Bitter disputes between the Kremlin and the three other victorious World War II Allies led to the Soviets move to cut <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> off from the West. Soviet dictator <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> was staunchly against creation of a unified German state in the three Western occupation zones, and when the Western allies backed a currency reform to speed up economic recovery of war-torn <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> imposed the blockade. Just four days after the money reform on June 20, the Soviets blocked all roads, waterways and railway lines leading to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> _ 110 miles deep in Soviet-occupied territory. In response, <PERSON> Clay </PERSON> ordered all cargo planes available to deliver provisions to keep the hope for democracy in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> alive. The continuous string of small C-47, C-54 and other cargo planes ferried about 120 tons of supplies to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> daily at the start. By April 1949, the `` Raisin Bombers,'' so-called because the crews often brought along candy and raisins for <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s hungry children, were bringing in about 13,000 tons of supplies a day. After the Soviets called off the blockade on May 12, 1949, the Western allies continued the flights to the end of September until normal land, waterway and rail traffic had resumed. More than 277,000 flights were conducted during the airlift, costing $ 200 million.
