<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Plutonium     06-23 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Plutonium,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Say Figures Confirm Two Tons of Plutonium Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists campaigning against nuclear weapons say new calculations confirm that about 2.3 tons of plutonium produced in British civil nuclear reactors is missing. But authorities say the scientists have misunderstood the problem and gotten their figures wrong. In a letter published today in Nature, a science weekly, an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and three British scientists say their 1985 claim of a shortfall is borne out by more detailed figures which the government began publishing last year. They say they do n't know where the missing plutonium has gone, but speculate that it went to nuclear weapons programs in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or both. The letter to Nature is signed by physicists <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnham </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Imperial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>; <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> of the pressure group Scientists Against Nuclear Arms; <PERSON> Jenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Bristol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>; and <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Unicam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, Aptox, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The problem centers on a 6.8-ton gap between government civil stockpiles, and the amount the scientists calculate actually were produced. The scientists said they have calculated that four tons went to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in exchange for enriched uranium under an agreement that lasted until 1971. About half a ton was lost in reprocessing, leaving 2.3 tons unaccounted for, they wrote. They said their 1985 calculations could not be confirmed because the government then was not disclosing figures. But when the government began publishing figures for each of its nine reactors, these coincided with the physicists' earlier calculations, proving their original model was correct, they wrote. Even so, the government figures are rounded out to the nearest 110 pounds of plutonium per reactor, which taken together would be enough to arm 100 warheads a year, <PERSON> Barnham </PERSON> said in an interview. <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Monk </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the government's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electricity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` The scientists' figures are inaccurate, because large numbers are involved and because they would appear to lack basic understanding of the processes involved.''
