<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nationwide survey of 1,400 hospital executives shows that 48 percent of them think reduced <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> reimbursements may force their hospitals to close in the next five years. Small, rural and government-owned hospitals in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> are most vulnerable, according to the survey conducted and paid for by the Boston-based Touche <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> accounting and management consulting firm. Suburban hospitals and hospitals owned by religious organizations also may be much more likely to close than in previous years, the survey showed. Hospitals in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> showed the greatest increase in the likelihood of closure, according to the study titled `` U.S. Hospitals: The Future of Health Care.'' In 1986, hospital executives estimated that 21 percent of their facilities might close. In the recent survey, the chance for closure jumped to 46 percent of local hospitals. `` The fact that so many hospitals anticipated failure is even more dramatic when one realizes that 150 hospitals have already closed in the last two years,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON>, national director of health services for <PERSON> Touche </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>. If the survey predictions are accurate, 680 hospitals will close in the next five years, he said. <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON> said the main reason for what the survey called American hospitals' `` increased vulnerability to failure'' is the decrease in revenues under the Medicare Prospective Payment system, a program created in 1983 to standardize the amounts <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> reimburses hospitals for in-patient care. Almost 70 percent of the hospital executives surveyed said hospital incomes have dropped since the program's inception. In contrast to small, rural and suburban hospitals, inner-city hospitals and other urban hospitals show no indication of a greater potential for closure since a 1986 survey, <PERSON> Cisneros </PERSON> said. Hospitals with the least chance of closure are located in the <LOCATION> mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> states and on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. Other findings of the survey: _ Occupancy rates are at an all-time low Forty-six percent of the hospitals surveyed reported average occupancy of less than 50 percent. _ The quality of care was perceived as declining In 1986, 55 percent of hospitals ranked the health care available in their regions as excellent, but in 1988 that number dropped to 44 percent. _ There are signs of increasing limitations on health-care delivery Three-fourths of the hospital officials questioned believe health care given patients should be curtailed when the cost of providing that care becomes excessive. Questionnaires were sent to hospital executives at all 5,678 acute-care hospitals in the country.
