<HEAD>Death Row Inmate Gets Stay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A death row inmate who faced execution Saturday won a 30-day stay on the same day that the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld the state's death penalty law. Convicted killer <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> got the stay Wednesday from a federal judge in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> because new attorneys in his case asked for more time. Also Wednesday, the high court announced its long-anticipated decision that it had voted 6-3 to uphold the conviction and death sentence of <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>. Attorneys for <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> had contended jurors were not allowed to consider any mitigating circumstances in sentencing <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> for the 1975 abduction-slaying of nurse <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Moran </PERSON>. Since the high court agreed to hear the case late last year, only one inmate, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Streetman </PERSON>, was put to death. Dozens of prisoners used the pending case to obtain stays of execution. After hearing of the high court decision Wednesday, death row inmates were predictably glum. <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>, 27, who had not yet heard of his stay was philosophical. `` If it's going to happen, it's going to happen,'' he said of the possibility of his death. Many inmates believed the Franklin case, the most serious challenge to the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> death penalty law in several years, would result in a ruling favorable to them and commutations of their sentences to life. `` I feel like an idiot having put my hopes in the court,'' inmate <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanderbilt </PERSON> said. `` This is a bitter disappointment. It's not easy seeing your friends hauled off to be killed. `` I'm afraid they'll try to get as many as they can before the next issue comes up,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Beathard </PERSON>, another death row resident. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> has turned down interviews since the ruling. His attorney, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, said he likely would seek a rehearing for <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> but that the high court rarely granted such motions. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said he doubted the pace of executions would quicken and speculated the court would analyze capital cases on a case-by-case basis. `` It's pretty nice when the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says you're right,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Walt </PERSON>, an assistant attorney general who handles death row cases. `` The plurality opinion is very close to what we said in our brief.'' <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> said it is likely <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> would be rescheduled for execution and the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> would vacate stays issued to other <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> inmates who cited the <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> case. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, which uses lethal injections, has executed 27 convicted killers, more than any other state since the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> allowed the death penalty to resume in 1976.
