<HEAD>Nearly 400 Pounds Of Cocaine Seized In Belgium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANTWERP, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police and customs agents seized nearly 400 pounds of cocaine worth $ 52.7 million in the past two days, officials said Thursday. Police said they seized 200 pounds worth $ 27.7 million early Wednesday aboard the Algerian freighter <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION>. They said a 37-year-old Canadian citizen, only identified as <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON>, was arrested. Authorities later Wednesday found 169 pounds of cocaine worth $ 25 million after the arrest of a Colombian living in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, identified as <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Torres-Lanos </PERSON>. Police said they began chasing two men after spotting them aboard the Japanese freighter <ORGANIZATION> Caribbean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maru </ORGANIZATION>. They said the two fled by car toward the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> but the car crashed into a truck. Torres-Lanos was arrested but the other man escaped, police said. Police said they found 55 pounds of cocaine in the car, another 68 pounds near the Japanese ship and 46 more pounds aboard the ship.
