<FIRST>u i AM-Rybakov Bjt   06-23 1070</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rybakov, Bjt,1101</SECOND>
<HEAD>Author Remained Patient Through Publishing Delays</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON>, author of `` Children of the Arbat,'' is in the front rank of those struggling to reform the Soviet system, a system which sent him to <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> in the 1930s and blocked publication of his novel for 21 years. His book, finally published in Russian last year, has recently appeared in English and his been critically acclaimed.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEREDELKINO, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Naumovich </PERSON> <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON>, still energetic at 77, jumped up and pulled a bundle of papers from one of the shelves that line the study of his cottage in the forested writers' colony outside <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Carefully, lovingly, the novelist laid the bundle on the desk next to the window, untied the string and pulled out two covers of the largest Soviet literary magazine, Novy Mir, one from 1966 and the other from 1978. In the soft light, filtered through the trees, <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON> held up first one and then the other of the blue sheets of stiff paper, tracing with his gnarled finger the underlined announcement that the journal would soon publish `` Children of the Arbat,'' his novel of the Great Terror waged by dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> in the 1930s. Both times, in 1966 and 1978, publication was blocked by the men in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, men who rose to power under <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON>'s patience paid off. More than 21 years after it was written, `` Children of the Arbat'' was published last year in the literary journal <ORGANIZATION> Druzhba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Narodov </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Friendship of Peoples -RRB-, as part of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s campaign to reform the tyrannical system created by <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> The novel has since appeared in hardback editions, and was published in English in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last month by Little, <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The book probes more deeply than any other yet published in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> into <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s mind and methods, the pettiness and arbitrariness that guided his followers, the innocence of his victims and the terror he created. It tells the story of <PERSON> Sasha </PERSON> <PERSON> Pankratov </PERSON>, a young man of 23 who, like <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON>, was sentenced without trial for a crime he never committed and sent to <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> for three years of cold and lonely exile. <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON> grew up in the apartment building inhabited by most of the book's characters, No. 51 Arbat Street, an old shopping street in downtown <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that was at once popular among the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> elite and among fashionable young people. <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON> is working on the sequel, `` 1935 and Other Years,'' which will continue the story, and like `` Children of the Arbat,'' will give intimate portraits of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and his lieutenants and describe how he terrorized his deputies and the country. `` The entire nation lived in fear,'' said <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON>, his craggy features grim beneath a balding pate and gray hair. `` Only one person thought for himself. Everyone else abandoned free thought.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his supporters have concluded that a nation based on such a system can not survive in the technological age. During the years <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON> waited for his blockbuster to appear in print, he lived and worked at his peaceful dacha, or cottage, at <LOCATION> Peredelkino </LOCATION>, the wooded village where the Nobel Prize-winning poet and novelist <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Pasternak </PERSON> wrote and is buried. <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON> earned a comfortable living by writing 11 other novels, as well as screenplays for television and movies. He resisted the temptation to publish his works abroad, as <PERSON> Pasternak </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aleksandr </PERSON> <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> and others had done. <PERSON> Pasternak </PERSON> was ostracized, his works banned until recently, and <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> was exiled to the West. `` I wanted to publish it in this country,'' said <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON>. `` I wanted to change my country. That is why I have been so patient.'' Hardback and paperbound editions of the book are expected to reach 3.5 million copies, he said, a phenomenal circulation in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where a run of 100,000 is considered generous for works of fiction. The book disappears from stores before it reaches the shelves. The only places it can be found in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> are in hotel shops open only to foreigners and at a special store on <PERSON> Kropotkin </PERSON> Street that accepts no rubles, only Western currency. On the black market, it sells for 30 rubles -LRB- $ 51.40 -RRB-, more than 10 times its retail price. Inside the <PERSON> Kropotkin </PERSON> store, a saleswoman told an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> visitor, `` I'm sorry. We do n't have ` Children of the Arbat.' It has n't come in yet.'' Then she lowered her voice. `` I'll get you a copy. But just one.'' She disappeared, returning a few minutes later with the volume. The written word has played a huge role in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> since the 19th century, when works by writers such as <LOCATION> Pushkin </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Tolstoy </PERSON> were a moral and spiritual counterbalance to the authoritarian rule of the Czars. The influence of writers in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is immensely greater than that of any American author in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` I do n't think that fiction is as important in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in shaping the image of a country in the minds of the people,'' said <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON>, just back from a month-long trip to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, his third visit in as many years. In reforming the Soviet system, said <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON>, `` the first step is to change the psychology of the people. Perestroika -LRB- restructuring -RRB- started in literature, films, the mass media, the fields that shape people's spiritual lives and thinking.'' `` We need to reshape people's minds, and that will inevitably lead us to economic freedom,'' said <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON>. `` Children of the Arbat'' deals largely with the purges within the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and only mentions in passing a far bloodier episode _ the 1929-32 collectivization of agriculture _ which caused a famine and, according to estimates by Western scholars, claimed 8 million lives. <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON> said he will explore this in greater depth in his next novel. `` My figures are even higher,'' he said. Although food shortages persist, six decades later Soviet authors have only tentatively touched on the collectivization issue. Any detailed discussion might lead to calls to return the land to private farmers, a step reformers in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have taken. <PERSON> Rybakov </PERSON> lets a grin crease his leathery face: `` I am no expert on decollectivization, but we need greater freedom in the village.'' The smile gives way again to a look of grim determination. `` Who will take land and cultivate it if he fears that someone will take it away from him?''
</TEXT>
