<TEXT>
 Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVries </PERSON>, who performed the nation's first permanent artificial heart implant nearly six years ago, has resigned from <ORGANIZATION> Humana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, it was announced today. His resignation is effective Monday, according to a news release from <LOCATION> Humana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital-Audubon </LOCATION>, where the institute is based. <PERSON> DeVries </PERSON> had been the institute's physician consultant in cardiovascular surgery. <PERSON> DeVries </PERSON> indicated that with his decision last year to establish his own private practice, continuation as a member of the institute could create a competitive conflict with Dr. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lansing </PERSON>'s private practice, the release said In 1984, <PERSON> DeVries </PERSON> left the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> to join <PERSON> Lansing </PERSON>'s practice <PERSON> Lansing </PERSON> also founded the institute and serves as its director and chairman. <PERSON> DeVries </PERSON> performed the nation's first heart transplant in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on retired dentist <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, who received a Jarvik-7 artificial heart on Dec. 12, 1982. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> died 112 days later. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, a retired federal worker from <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, lived longest of anyone with the permanent implant, 620 days, after receiving a Jarvik-7 on Nov. 25, 1984.
