<HEAD>Unmanned Engines Run Through Three Towns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORANGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three unmanned locomotives today sped through three towns at speeds up to 40 mph before stopping on their own, officials said. The runaway engines traveled about 10 miles between the towns of <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> in north central <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. There were no injuries reported as a result of the runaway engines, said <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Pease </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Guilford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the trains. <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> said a crew working on engines near the Gardner rail yard discovered the string of locomotives was gone at about 5 a.m. and they notified a dispatcher, who alerted local authorities. He said he believes the trains were released by vandals, and he said it was at least the second runaway since another string of locomotives sped out of control through nine towns last November until they were deliberately slammed into empty freight cars in <LOCATION> Deerfield </LOCATION>. There were no injuries in that incident, and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said it has found no evidence of sabotage. <PERSON> Pease </PERSON>, however, said the two runaways and a third last January form a pattern that can not be coincidental. `` The circumstances are just too close,'' <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> said. `` Hopefully somebody will begin realizing this is a serious problem and that we need help.'' The latest incident came four days after striking rail workers began returning to work, ending a six-month walkout over safety issues. Union leader <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Maloof </PERSON> said today that the workers could not have been involved in the alleged vandalism because they were busy taking physical exams.
