<FIRST>r w AM-SeatBelts     06-23 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seat Belts,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private Study Concludes Back-Seat Lap Belts Are Risky</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rear-seat lap belts expose victims of car crashes to greater risk of paralysis or death than lap-and-shoulder restraints, according to a study released Thursday by product-liability lawyers. The <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Injury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reduction </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Dunkirk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, organization founded this year by attorneys involved in product-injury litigation, presented the study at a hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> government activities and transportation subcommittee. `` In crash after crash, children and adults are dying, being rendered paraplegic or quadriplegic or suffering disabling injuries to their abdominal organs while wearing only rear-seat lap belts,'' <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON>, president of the institute, testified. The tests commissioned by the institute were conducted by <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Testing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Liberty </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. The tests used instrumented dummies belted into the rear-seat assembly of a 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LX </ORGANIZATION> and subjected to simulated crashes. A 33 mph simulated crash using dummies the size of 6-year-old children showed pressure against the outer part of the lap belt when used alone was 61 percent greater than with a lap-shoulder combination. In a simulated crash at 27 mph using adult-size dummies, pressure on the outside part of the lap belt when used alone was 338 percent higher than with a lap-shoulder combination. A similar test at 32 mph showed a 145 percent difference. The results indicate `` a greater likelihood for lap-belt only occupants to sustain severe ... or fatal injuries in such crashes,'' the study said. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Sursi </PERSON>, program manager at Automotive Safety Testing, said in an interview the study did not address the question of the position of the lap belt on the passenger. Auto manufacturers and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> have said a properly adjusted lap belt will provide protection because the force of the crash will be absorbed by the large pelvic bones. A misadjusted belt will result in the belt's cutting through the soft abdomen to the spinal column, studies have shown. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION>'s policy is to encourage manufacturers voluntarily to install lap-and-shoulder belt combinations in the rear seat while asserting that a lap belt alone provides better crash protection than no belt. A 1986 study by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, however, concluded that lap belts used alone may cause serious injury rather than providing protection. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanna </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vehicle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents the nation's automakers, told the committee `` by 1990 virtually every car produced in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> will be equipped with lap-shoulder belts in outboard rear seating positions.'' Automakers offer kits for nearly all models made in the last 10 years that allow owners to install lap-should belt combinations in the back seat of vehicles, <PERSON> Hanna </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Injury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reduction </ORGANIZATION>, however, said knowledge and availability of such kits is limited. The institute, on May 25-26, conducted a random telephone poll of 30 dealers for five automakers in six cities and found none had lap-should belt kits in stock, 21 said no kits were available and only eight said kits could be ordered.
</TEXT>
