<HEAD>Pope Arrives In Austria For Controversial Visit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with pontiff's reference to Nazi
death camp, background on 50th anniversary of annexation with Nazi
Germany. Pickup 7th graf pvs, ``The Polish-born ...'' Minor editing
to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> today urged Austrians to remember its World War II past as he began a controversial trip that includes meetings with President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> and a visit to a former <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death camp. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, under bitter attack from Jews and shunned by most Western leaders for his alleged complicity in Nazi war crimes, led the official government welcoming delegation for the Roman Catholic leader. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, in his own greetings, denounced `` intolerance, intransigence and hate among nations, religions and classes,'' but made no direct comments about the dispute over his past as a German army officer. The white-robed pontiff's special <ORGANIZATION> Alitalia </ORGANIZATION> DC-9 aircraft touched down at <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>' <LOCATION> Schwechat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> during a light shower. In comments delievered in German, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> mentioned his second trip as pope to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> will include the site of the former <LOCATION> Mauthausen </LOCATION> death camp. He said such places recall `` times of hardship which have left their indelible mark. `` Let us, when we meet, bring before God not only the great and burdensome legacy of the past but also the joys and sorrows of the present,'' the pontiff said. Many Austrians claim they were victims of <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> rule, and the nation's events marking the 50th anniversary of the 1938 annexation with the Third Reich have sparked a renewed round of soul-searching. The Polish-born pontiff drew the ire of Jews when he received <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> a year ago at the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, an audience the pope later defended as `` necessary'' because <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> came as a democratically elected president. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> says the pope's meetings with world leaders do not imply his support for an individual or political system. `` This is not a political visit. It is a pastoral visit. He -LRB- the pope -RRB- was invited by the bishops,'' said <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON>. Today, six American Jews demonstrated outside <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s office to show their displeasure with the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s decision to meet with him. `` Do not embrace <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, no!'' said Rabbi <PERSON> Avi </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Riverdale </LOCATION>, N.Y. Standing with him were five Jewish students dressed in black-and-white striped uniforms reminiscent of those worn by concentration camp inmates during the Nazi era. Earlier this week, two representatives of major Jewish organizations met with a <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> envoy in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> to register their protests over the meetings. Dr. <PERSON> Avi </PERSON> <PERSON> Beker </PERSON> of the World Jewish <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> said the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> was `` going out of his way to legitimize <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>.'' But Rabbi <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanenbaum </PERSON>, director of international relations of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, warned against `` extremist hysteria and stridency'' over the meetings. In a statement from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Wednesday, he pointed out that the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> was visiting a predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> country and that it was <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> policy for popes to meet with heads of states of countries with which the Holy See has diplomatic relations. <PERSON> Tanenbaum </PERSON> also said his group had been informed by <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials that the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s contacts with <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> `` will be kept to an absolute minimum.'' <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> has denied that he committed war crimes, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has barred him, saying it found evidence he was involved in deportations of <LOCATION> Balkan </LOCATION> civilians in World War II. An international commission of historians appointed by the Austrian government to investigate the allegations concluded in February that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> was aware of Nazi atrocities in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> and did nothing to prevent them. It left open the question of whether he was guilty of wartime atrocities. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> is to deliver about 20 speeches during the trip, his second to a country where the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> counts 6.4 million Roman Catholics, or 85 percent of the 7.5 million population. He paid a three-day visit in 1983. On Friday, the 68-year-old pontiff is scheduled to meet with representatives of <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s 12,000 Jews, then visit the site of the <LOCATION> Mauthausen </LOCATION> concentration camp where 110,000 prisoners died during World War II. On pilgrimages to his homeland, the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> visited the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Majdanek </LOCATION> death camps.
