<HEAD>Landmark Leans A Little Bit More</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PISA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The famed leaning tower tilted another fraction of an inch in the past year, a rate that might cause the landmark to topple in about 100 years, an expert said Thursday. <PERSON> Gero </PERSON> <PERSON> Geri </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pisa </ORGANIZATION> said that since June 1987 the tower has leaned 0.05 inches, according to measurments taken Wednesday. <PERSON> Geri </PERSON> is a member of the team which makes semi-annual checks of the displacement of several of <LOCATION> Pisa </LOCATION>'s architectural treasures, settling into the city's soft clay foundation. Although December's check-up showed encouraging signs that the tower's tilt may be slowing, <PERSON> Geri </PERSON> said Wednesday's readings indicated the monument had resumed its average tilting pace of about 0.04 inches per year. The 180-foot tower, completed between 1360 and 1370, is now leaning 14.6 feet off the vertical. `` We really do not know why it's still standing,'' <PERSON> Geri </PERSON> said. `` But judging from its current rate of shift and from the centuries the process has taken, we estimate that the structure will fall in a century if nothing is done to stop it.'' He added: `` No one is really sure when it will go down.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> has been trying for years to come up with a plan to save the tower, but any project is far from implementation.
