<HEAD>Midwest Governors Meet On Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Expanding federal crop insurance and diverting <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> to allow resumption of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> barge traffic are among the steps needed to deal with the drought, speakers today told Midwestern governors. `` We'll need a little bit of time to determine what the losses are,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>. `` But we will do what is needed to minimize the severity of the damage.'' The 10 governors at the meeting told <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> about a number of problems. Illinois Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said his state's soybean and corn crops would be lost without substantial rain in the next 30 days, while Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> said 70 percent of his state's grain crop already is lost. `` Welcome to the heart of the drought land,'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said in opening the conference. `` We used to be known as the heart of the heartland. Now we are both.'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said barge traffic _ much of it bringing crops to market _ is virtually closed on the vital commercial waterway of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, and he called for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> to petition the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and allow diversion of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> water in order to get the traffic flowing again. <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON> said the one-day conference would address how to prevent farmers struggling because of the drought from going broke and leaving the land and devising a long-term solution to dropping water tables throughout the northern tier and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said the federal government's response would include expansion of existing crop insurance and disaster loan programs. He also cited the creation of task forces in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and within President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s administration preparing to respond to problems of the drought. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> left the conference after his speech, but said he would meet with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Friday morning to update him on the drought situation. Attending the day-long meeting, besides Sinner and <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, were the governors of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebaska </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> announced a toll-free number for farmers affected by the drought and seeking federal help. The number is 1-800-541-3375.
