<HEAD>Mofford Says She's Feeling Better, Intends To Run in 1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> says she is recovering from the concussion she suffered a month ago and still intends to run for governor in 1990. `` I've made the bend and am starting to feel better again,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> said during a two-hour appearance Wednesday at the <ORGANIZATION> Tucson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rotary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, her first public outing of more than three minutes since her injury in a fall. At one point, she raised her arms and emphatically told the luncheon audience, `` If I did n't quit when I became acting governor, I'm not gon na quit now.'' She took office upon the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s conviction April 4 of impeached Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>. She joked about her fall off a dais in <LOCATION> Yuma </LOCATION>, saying, `` Today is exactly one month that the <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cardinals </ORGANIZATION> were trying to sign me up.'' In the incident, <ORGANIZATION> Cardinals </ORGANIZATION>' Coach <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON> accidentally grabbed onto her as he fell backward, knocking her from her chair and causing her to hit her head. The 66-year-old governor said her doctor has told her to limit her activity, but she added, `` I'm doing pretty good and I'm making a good comeback. That was quite a fall.''
