<HEAD>Moscow Synagogue to Acquire Building It Lost During War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City officials agreed Thursday to return a building now used as a medical institute to the synagogue that owned it before World War II, two <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and Soviet rabbis announced. `` We asked for this five years ago, 15 and 20 years ago, but no one would listen,'' the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s chief rabbi, <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Shayevich </PERSON>, said in an interview. The return of the two-story building to the Choral Synagogue on <LOCATION> Arkhipova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> fits a pattern of liberalization that began during preparations for the celebration of the 1,000 th anniversary of Christianity in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> During the celebration earlier this month, the government returned a monastery it had controlled in <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> and several churches throughout the country to the Russian Orthodox Church. The Soviet government has taken over church property since the 1920s. After the structure was built more than 100 years ago, the synagogue used it for Jewish community activities, but the government took it away in 1941 and made it into a hospital for World War II casualties, <PERSON> Shayevich </PERSON> said. It now houses a training center for doctors. It is adjacent to the beige synagogue, and the two doors connecting it to the synagogue are sealed. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneier </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> rabbi, said he began campaigning 1 -LCB- years ago for the return of the building but made progress with Soviet officials just in the past two weeks, during the millennium of Christianity. `` It's part of a process that seeks to align religious believers with restructuring and rebuilding of society,'' <PERSON> Schneier </PERSON> said in an interview in a synagogue office. `` They are trying to reach out to the masses.'' He said the return of the building `` would have been unthinkable'' during his first visit in 1966 and `` improbable five years ago.'' <PERSON> Schneier </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s deputy mayor, <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arzhanov </PERSON>, agreed on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> Thursday to turn over the building to the synagogue. The oral agreement is to be followed up with a formal contract later. <PERSON> Schneier </PERSON> said the Jewish congregation he represents at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Synagogue </LOCATION> will help pay for restoration of the building and will send architects and construction specialists to offer advice. He predicted the building could be used within two years for adult Jewish education classes and a museum. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> synagogue also has agreed to help the medical institute find other quarters, <PERSON> Schneier </PERSON> said.
