<HEAD>Phone Problems Bedevil House of Representatives</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Donnald is correct in 13th graf, ``House Clerk''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House of Representatives telephone system went dead Thursday for the fourth time in two weeks, silencing half of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and leading one lawmaker to complain that <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> would be `` depressed and despondent.'' The widespread outage brought howls from congressmen cut off from their constituents and district offices, and prompted a scramble by top officials of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which installed the $ 16 million system, to find out what went wrong. `` I do n't know what motivated this installation of the new system, but it's certainly proven to be a failure,'' Rep. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.C. </LOCATION>, complained. Had Bell, the inventor of the telephone, been around during the last two weeks, he `` would have been most depressed and despondent, to say nothing of being embarrassed,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolbe </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ariz </LOCATION>., said the communications glitch reminded him of the <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T television commercials showing distraught employees bemoaning their choice of a phone system and discussing how their businesses had been ruined The commercials end by proclaiming <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T `` the right choice.'' `` Well, in the interest of ... truth in advertising, I think we ought to admit that the same source of that advertising is the one that has the telephone system here in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Kolbe </PERSON> said in a floor speech. When the system went down for the first time last week, he said, `` it was kind of nice to have the break. No calls coming in, quiet in the offices. Everybody went off and got a <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> or did something.'' But as the outages kept recurring, he said, `` tempers increased.'' Members and staff described variously everything from totally dead telephones to intermittent operation of some lines. Calls could not be transferred. At times, all the lights on a telephone would go on at once and all the phones in an office would ring simultaneously. Officials in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> clerk's office, which administers the phone system, said they were working feverishly to find out what had gone wrong and that <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T had sent its top technical experts from all over the country to help diagnose the problem. `` It's a flukey sort of thing,'' said Deputy House Clerk <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Colley </PERSON>. The switching system which is the heart of the telephone network is a computerized AT & amp; T System 85, which is in wide use and has not been a problem elsewhere, he said. <PERSON> Colley </PERSON> said he believed the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> system, which has some 17,000 telephones, is one of the largest in the country. `` We're losing a lot of calls, obviously,'' he said. `` Believe me, we have total attention from <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T.'' Technicians suspected a software problem but were examining everything, including the possibility of computer hackers tampering with the system from outside, he said. An <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T spokesman, <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Linnen </PERSON>, said the company had pulled together its best technical minds and was working `` around the clock'' to resolve the problem. `` We do not know the cause. We have tried to replicate the calling situation of the House in our Bell Lab facilities in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> to see if we can spot a software or hardware problem, but we have not been able to replicate it,'' he said. <PERSON> Linnen </PERSON> said the company was `` totally empathetic'' with lawmakers' frustration. `` We are frustrated. We have a commitment to get the ... problem fixed as quickly as possible,'' he said. The system was installed last August, and after some initial startup problems worked fine until it went dead for the first time last week, <PERSON> Colley </PERSON> said. Since then, outages of an hour or more occurred on Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday. House Clerk <PERSON> Donnald </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> defended the system. `` We've got the best system on the market,'' he said. `` I still have confidence in System 85.'' Meantime, <PERSON> Kolbe </PERSON> had a suggestion for members frustrated by being unable to communicate with constituents: use the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor and its television system as an `` electronic billboard'' to send open messages back home. `` And if nothing else works, my staff has come up with a prototype system,'' he said, holding up a pair of styrofoam coffee cups linked by a piece of wire. `` If I get the contract for $ 10 million or so to install this in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, I promise that it will work just as well as the phone system we have here now.''
