<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> welcomed on Thursday what it hoped was a `` flexible approach'' by <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> toward negotiations to end a 13-year-old war between Cuban-backed government forces and U.S.-supported guerrillas. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>, noting reports that the Angolan government is willing to enter peace discussions without demanding cessation of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for the rebels, said `` we welcome a flexible approach to these very complex problems we're addressing.'' His comments were made on the eve of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION>, South African and Angolan talks in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> on a possible settlement of the conflict that has enflamed southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> for more than a decade. One of the stumbling blocks in recent years has been <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s unwillingness to negotiate a withdrawal of Cuban forces in the country as long as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> backed the guerrilla forces of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> receives more than $ 15 million a year in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance. In Thursday editions, The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> quoted Angolan Justice Minister <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Franca </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunem </PERSON> as saying <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> would not be an issue in the talks about to begin. `` It is not appropriate for us to raise the issue now,'' the minister said. `` We will raise it with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> separately, at another juncture. The issue is not on the table for the current negotiations. We should not mix these subjects.'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said that `` the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position has always been that that is not a subject for discussion and it has never been on the table in these negotiations.'' The American spokesman also said Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> would meet next week with <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON>. After <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> met with the Angolan government delegation on Wednesday, the department issued a statement declaring `` the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> believes that the quickest way to end the conflict that has already consumed the lives of thousands of Angolans, is for Angolans themselves to meet and resolve their differences peacefully and without the pressures and interference of outside forces.''
