<HEAD>Second Day of News Strike Keeps Papers Off Stands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nationwide journalists' strike, in its second day on Thursday, kept nearly all of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s national newspapers off the newstands and reduced state-run broadcasts to bare-bone accounts. The contract dispute also stilled news agencies, including the two major national ones, <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> AGI </ORGANIZATION>. Among the missing papers were the leading sports dailies, but for soccer fans, it was probably just as well. The strike meant no post-mortems of Wednesday's night match between <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which saw the Soviets kill the Italians' title hopes for the European championship. The state broadcasting network RAI had carried the match live to show the journalists' `` sensibility'' to the nation's soccer fever. The broadcast, which involves the services of journalists, was the only exception on Wednesday to the no-work day. On Thursday, however, <ORGANIZATION> RAI </ORGANIZATION> radio and television carried reduced newscsts, without video or audio services. Instead, an announcer designated by the journalists' union read the news in reduced form, including a declaration of why the strike was called. The strike was scheduled to end Friday, allowing the publication of Saturday's newspapers. Local papers and some that are outside the union, such as the leftist Manifesto, did publish. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> called the strike, which began Wednesday morning, over a breakdown in negotiations. Publishers and union officials have agreed on a $ 381 monthly pay increase in the new contract. But the unions are want a clause preventing newspaper chains from using a central newsroom to provide national and international news for the group, and publishers say that would be too costly.
