<HEAD>Corporate Profits Dip 1 Percent in First Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's businesses reported a 1.0 percent decline in profits after taxes in the first three months of this year, the poorest performance in a year, the government said Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said profits dipped to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 144.2 billion, down $ 1.4 billion from the last three months of 1987. It was sharpest drop since the first quarter of 1987, when profits fell 3.7 percent. In the second and third quarters of last year, after-tax earnings rose 4.3 percent and 5.5 percent, respectively. Thursday's report on the January-March period represents a downward revision from an estimate last month, when the department said profits after taxes rose 0.5 percent. Many analysts believe lagging profits are a sign of inflation because they expect companies to raise prices to make up for lost ground. However, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Straszheim </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION>, said he believed most companies, remembering the painful cutbacks they had to make when imports flooded the country in the early 1980s, will be very cautious about boosting prices. `` I think companies are going to take a bit of a longer-term view and say, ` Wait a minute, if we raise prices too quickly, we may give some of that market share back to our foreign competitors,''' he said. In other details of the report, the government said: _ Corporate cash flows, a measurement intended to show the funds corporations have for investment, rose 0.6 percent to an annual rate of $ 378.8 billion after a 0.5 percent increase in the fourth quarter _ Dividend payments to stockholders rose 2.1 percent to an annual rate of $ 99.3 billion in the first quarter following a 2.2 percent increase in the fourth quarter _ Corporate profits before taxes were down 1.4 percent to $ 281.5 billion annual level in the first quarter following a 0.2 percent increase in the fourth quarter
