<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two paddle-wheelers take off Friday for the annual re-creation of a historic steamboat race, but the drought that's drying up the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> could prompt officials to eliminate some ports of call. The 10-day trip still will begin on schedule, said Capt. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Keeton </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> Queen. <PERSON> Keeton </PERSON> said Thursday that river traffic was being shut down at <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, to allow for dredging of the shallow river channel. But by the time the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Queen </LOCATION> and its rival <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Queen </ORGANIZATION> reach that point, the river may be open, he said. `` Hopefully, we'll be thre just at the right place at the right time,'' <PERSON> Keeton </PERSON> said. The company that operates both steamships said planned stops at <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Carthersville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, may have to be changed. Both ships are scheduled to steam into the port at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, under the <ORGANIZATION> Gateway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arch </ORGANIZATION>, at 9 a.m. on the Fourth of July. Among precautions being taken by the steamship company to assure safe navigation of the shallower river will be the use of a towboat pushing a barge with a 9-foot draft. The tow and barge will travel ahead of the steamships, acting as a pathfinder. The `` race'' pits the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> Queen against the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Queen </ORGANIZATION> in what is billed as a re-enactment of the June 24, 1870, race between the <LOCATION> Natchez </LOCATION> and the <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>. However, instead of trying to match the speed of that race _ which was won by the <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> in three days, 18 hours and 14 minutes _ the two modern-day steamboats will set a leisurely 10-day pace. The boats traditionally stop at <LOCATION> Natchez </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> and other ports where passengers and crew from each vessel take part in contests such as `` dueling calliopes,'' the `` Floozie Parade Competition'' and a kite flying contest. Points gained during all the events determine the winner of the `` race.''
