<HEAD>Big Trade Bill Lands In Senate Hopper Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plant Closing Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senators dumped an overhauled version of their vetoed, 1,000-page bill in the hopper Thursday and expressed optimism that the measure will reach President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s desk this year. `` This represents a consensus on trade policy _ it's a consensus that has been a long time in coming,'' Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo., told reporters <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said he saw `` an excellent chance of getting trade legislation and I'm optimistic. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said, however, that there would not be time to take up the legislation at least until late He said he wants to get all of the fiscal 1989 money bills through the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> first. That timetable threatened to put the slimmed-down trade bill in a time squeeze, with some lawmakers opposed to any such legislation while others may be eager to wrap up congressional business and hit the campaign trail. A similar bill quietly went into the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> hopper last week and there were signs that it might see faster action. The measure is shorn of a provision that would require companies to provide 60-day notice of plant closings and major layoffs. As the lawmakers fielded questions at a news conference, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debated a separate plant-closings bill with provisions identical to those removed from the trade bill. A similar plant-closings measure was pending in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, and lawmakers in both houses planned to vote on the measure before the July Fourth break. Democratic leaders have been saying for three weeks that prospects appear good for passage of separate plant-closings legislation. Labor unions had lobbied against detaching the plant-closings provision from the trade bill in April and refused to give in when <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders asked them to go along with dropping it. The leaders then pushed the bill with the provision intact despite predictions that it meant a sure veto. This time union leaders again lobbied against detaching the plant-closings provision. But Democratic leaders insisted on doing so, a move that insulates them from election-year charges of refusing to compromise on trade. Also dropped from the modified version of the trade bill were provisions to restrict <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> petroleum exports. They would limit exports from new oil refineries in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> to 70,000 barrels a day and 50 percent of output. Up to 50,000 barrels a day could be exported to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> but only after making a detour in an American-flagged vessel to a port in the lower 48 states. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> objected to both the plant-closings and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil provisions in his veto of the earlier version of the legislation. Central features of the measure would overhaul the system under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposes import curbs to aid threatened <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries and retaliate against international trade violations. Other features range from repeal of the 1980 windfall profits tax on oil industry earnings to substantial agricultural subsidy programs. One feature targeted in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto message but left intact when seantors overhauled their measure would allow duty-free imports of <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> ethanol, used for making gasohol. Corn producers have been fighting to get it erased. `` All you have to do is look at the drought,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. `` ... They're not going to have the corn for ethanol.'' <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> appealed for support from farm groups. `` This bill is very good farm legislation,'' he said. `` As a matter of fact I think it is the most significant agricultural legislation that I've ever seen in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>.'' It would provide $ 1.5 billion in payments to grain companies to spur exports as well as millions of dollars to agribusinesses to advertise their wares in global markets. Under the measure, wheat, feed grains and oilseed crop producers would receive stepped-up subsidies aimed at stimulating global sales if negotiators fail to make progress on farm issues in the current <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round of world trade talks.
