<HEAD>Government Approves Homosexuals' Association</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to CORRECT that association not the first
in East bloc.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has approved in principle the registration of an association for homosexuals, a member of parliament said Thursday. <PERSON> Mikolaj </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozakiewicz </PERSON>, a prominent sexologist and member of parliament from the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> peasant <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview that he was told by the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> that homosexual associations may be formed for different cities in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. It would be the second association for homosexuals in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bloc </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> approved a similar association several months ago after much public debate. The Polish associations will have the right to their own publications and will be `` linked in some way to the public health service,'' he said. According to <PERSON> Kozakiewicz </PERSON>, there are about 30 male homosexuals in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> who are willing to join the association, and a much larger group which would support it. <PERSON> Kozakiewicz </PERSON> said he was approached last year by a small group of homosexuals and was asked for help in winning permission for an association. He said he met personally with Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, minister of the interior, to discuss the matter. He received word that it was approved Wednesday from Deputy Health Minister <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonczak </PERSON>, he said. Homosexuality is legal in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and persecution of homosexuals is unheard of. But it is much less open than in Western countries and homosexuals have complained of intolerance and bigotry. For the first time in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> last year, four representatives of the nascent gay movement appeared on television, on a late-night talk show `` Intimate Talks.'' They spoke frankly about their problems, but appeared only with their backs to the camera. The unwillingness of homosexuals to identify themselves has been considered one obstacle to the government's efforts to combat the AIDS virus in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Homosexuals have been asked to volunteer for blood tests under an ambitious government program to counter the disease, which has claimed at least three lives in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.
