<FIRST>u w AM-FCC-Indecency Bjt   06-23 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FCC-Indecency, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missouri TV Station First To Be Fined Under New `Indecency' Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> voted Thursday to impose the first fine under its decency standards on a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> television station for broadcasting a `` pandering and titillating'' sex comedy during prime time. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> voted 2-1 to levy the maximum $ 2,000 fine on KZKC-TV, a UHF station in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, for showing the movie `` Private Lessons'' at 8 p.m., a time at which the agency said children were likely to be watching. The movie, broadcast May 26, 1987, is about a 15-year-old boy who is seduced by his housekeeper and included scenes in which the woman appeared bare-breasted. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said the scenes `` were neither isolated nor fleeting.'' The commission said that while nudity and sexual themes are not necessarily `` indecent,'' their context and treatment in `` Private Lessons'' were. `` The movie included nudity and scenes depicting sexual matters which were dealt with in a pandering and titillating manner,'' the commission said. `` The story line of the seduction of a 15-year-old boy by an older woman, together with the inclusion of explicit nudity, would have commanded the attention of children and the sexual references would have been readily understood by children who tuned into the program,'' the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said. Attorney <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, representing <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, owner of KZKC-TV, said he was `` shocked and surprised and outraged by the imposition of the maximum fine in light of the circumstances.'' <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON> said the punishment was unfair because the standards are vague and this is the first time they have been applied to television. `` We do n't know what is indecent because the standard does n't provide any guidance,'' he said The guidelines are being challenged in court by broadcasting groups, news organizations and public interest advocates as being unconstitutionally vague and overbroad. Media Central has not decided what action to take, <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON> said. Station officials have said the movie was edited for television by an inexperienced editor and violated its own standards for good taste but that they took immediate corrective action, including clarification of the station's policy on nudity. All three commissioners agreed that the movie was indecent and that children are likely to be in the audience before midnight, but Commissioner <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> said the commission has no evidence there is a substantial number of unsupervised children in the audience at that time. `` Parents, not the commission, should bear the primary responsibility of deciding what their children should watch at night,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said surveys have shown that 42 percent of all children are watching TV at 8 p.m. and that `` it is reasonable to assume that there are unsupervised children in the audience.'' Commissioner <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Quello </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s action was significant because `` this serves notice that we are going to enforce indecency standards'' in regard to television as well as radio stations. It marked the first indecency finding against a TV station and was the first time the agency imposed a fine under its tough new standards. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> decided in April 1987 to toughen its existing decency standards by applying the wording of a 1978 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision that said indecent material is `` language or material that depicts or describes, in terms patently offensive as measured by contemporary community standards for the broadcast medium, sexual or excretory activities or organs.'' The commission said indecent material may be aired only when there is a reasonable risk that children are not in the audience. In a subsequent ruling in November 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said it would consider that children were not likely to be in the audience after midnight. Previously the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> had considered 10 p.m. the cutoff time.
</TEXT>
