 <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> Alimenti </PERSON>, a journalist who covered the papacy for <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s state-run television for 10 years, died Thursday after suffering a stroke a week ago during an on-air interview at the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. He was 54. Alimenti reported on most of Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>'s trips abroad and in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, and had been scheduled to travel with the pontiff to <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> on Thursday. Last week, he suffered a stroke while interviewing <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON>, collapsing while millions of Italians heard his voice trail off on the main evening news program. <PERSON> Alimenti </PERSON> joined the RAI network in 1962. He is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Giuseppina </PERSON>, and a daughter.
