<HEAD>Jackson Won't Divulge Private Decision on Veep Question</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: May be topped</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Thursday he has decided in his own mind whether he wants to be <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' running mate, but said he has not shared that decision with the likely Democratic presidential nominee. After reiterating his stance that he has earned serious consideration for the post, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was asked if he has privately decided whether he wants the job. `` Privately, yes,'' he replied. But as to informing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on his point of view, he said teasingly, `` No, that would be public.'' He made the comments to reporters after a pre-convention meeting with his state campaign chairmen from around the country who are in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for briefings on convention strategy and planning. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> then departed for <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, where he plans a series of appearances over the next three days. <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> has been an object of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> complaints about unfair distribution of delegates during the primary season. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> won <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>'s non-binding `` beauty contest'' primary, but all 57 delegates were awarded to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said Thursday that `` no doubt there will be some adjustments made in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>'' in delegate distribution as there has been in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, other states where he objected to the way delegates were allocated. The island's governor, <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON>, said Thursday he was considering <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s request for some of the delegates. <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON> said `` we are willing to examine a petition of that nature within the context of the need for unity in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and always, in coordination with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' campaign. <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON> also said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> `` should be seriously considered for the position -LRB- of vice president -RRB- since he won second place in the primaries all over the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>'s 3.2 million people are <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens but do not vote in general elections. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was asked here whether he thinks <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is giving him fair and serious consideration for the vice presidential spot. He said the process is ongoing. `` So far we are a part of the process. The process is one thing. The conclusion ... is another,'' he said. He said, however, that so far, `` I feel positive about it. I feel hopeful about it.'' Regarding the non-publicized criteria that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is using to pick a running mate, he said, `` Some judgment must be made on some criteria which has not yet been established.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> listed his own baseline criteria for a running mate _ ability to inspire youth, experience in the Third World and ability to erase traditional discrimination based on race or sex. Although the focus for weeks has been on <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s vice presidential aspirations, he is refusing to follow the other runnerup candidates in endorsing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> before the convention. `` That's somebody trying to get me to play some rules that are not in the interest of my constituency,'' he said. `` My constituency has a reason to continue our campaign to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'' and take an active role in the platform, rules and credentials committees. He said he would endorse the ticket `` at the appropriate time,'' if he loses the nomination, and said that `` those who have thrown in the towel early, they are people who have fainted in the face of adversity.''
