<SECOND>AM-Maryland Motto,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Works To Change Maryland State Motto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> discovered <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s motto when their son wrote a history report, and began another campaign to persuade the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> to change a motto they consider sexist. The motto in Italian, `` Fatti maschii parole femine,'' means `` Manly deeds and womanly words,'' according to the state's accepted translation `` There it was right on the seal. ... It is pretty disgusting,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> said recently. She and her husband have formed MOMMA, or Modernization of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Motto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Since mid-May about 400 people have signed the <ORGANIZATION> Wolfes </ORGANIZATION>' petition, which hangs on the cash register at their College Park store, the Smile Herb Shop. They hope to have 3,000 signatures on the petition when they submit it to state officials. The Wolfes are not the first to try to change the motto. In 1978, a joint resolution requested a legislative committee to devise `` a more appropriate state motto.'' `` The motto is incompatible with the equal rights and privileges accorded to women by the Constitution of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' read the bill, which died in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. During the past three centuries, scholars have debated the motto's proper translation. `` Deeds are of more avail than words'' and `` Act boldly but speak softly'' are among the less offensive translations, said <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Stiverson </PERSON>, former editor of <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manual </ORGANIZATION>, a handbook of state government. <PERSON> Stiverson </PERSON> believes a corrupt translation has created the motto's sexist slant While he favors a change in the traditional translation, he said state legislative action may prove difficult. Legislators argued at length a few years ago about whether `` maschii'' should be spelled with a single `` i,'' a double `` i'' or end in the letters `` ij.'' In their campaign, the <ORGANIZATION> Wolfes </ORGANIZATION> contacted their legislator, Delegate <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON>. `` Frankly I'm not convinced the motto itself is sexist,'' <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON> said, `` but if it is, we ought to change it.'' He said a bill would most likely change the translation, not the motto. `` My concern is to just change it so that deeds and words are not related to gender ... and so -LRB- the motto -RRB- says something positive,'' <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> said.
