<HEAD>Central Committee May Get New Members, Agenda Not Clear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Next week's <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference may name new members to the policy-setting <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, but it will stick to the old practice of closing the door on most of its debates, an official said Thursday. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sklyarov </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Propaganda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the conference, opening Tuesday, could name new members to the 300-plus member party body that formulates policy and signs off on key personnel changes between the party congresses, which normally are held every five years. But he did not say definitely that there would be new members to replace so-called `` dead souls'' _ 60 to 70 members who have died or lost the jobs that entitled them to <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> seats since the last party congress in 1986. For many months after <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> announced in January 1987 that he would hold the first party conference since 1941, Soviet officials and journalists predicted it would make sweeping changes in the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to give the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader a body strongly backing his reforms. The strength of conservatives who are braking change appears to have scaled down the expectations of a sweeping personnel shakeup and radical reforms. Many <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> intellectuals now say they expect the conference to be more of a dress rehearsal for a pro-reform congress in 1991, saying <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> may have learned from this experience how to do to avoid conservative maneuvering to dominate delegate slates. <PERSON> Sklyarov </PERSON> said Thursday that live television coverage of the conference will be limited to a broadcast of the opening session, where <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will set the tone with a report on the present and future pace of reform, and a report on the closing session. Delegate speeches will be summarized on TV and printed in full in newspapers once the speakers themselves have had a chance to approve the text, <PERSON> Sklyarov </PERSON> said. The arrangements are almost identical to those for the February 1986 congress and seem certain to disappoint the most outspoken reformers who had demanded live TV coverage of the entire meeting as a way of making the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> more accountable to the people it rules. Strengthening political accountability and the legal system are two declared goals of the 30-page conference proposals, known as theses, which have been fiercely debated in the media and at party meetings since being approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> May 23. The theses contain proposals that could dismantle the vestiges of Stalinism, but are vaguely worded in a possible attempt to fend off conservatives. <PERSON> Sklyarov </PERSON> said hundreds of thousands of suggestions based on the theses have poured into the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which is collating them for presentation to the agenda-setting presidium of the conference. He declined to specify, however, who is collating the proposals and exactly how the presidium will be selected. <ORGANIZATION> Georgian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> head <PERSON> Dzhumber </PERSON> <PERSON> Patiashvili </PERSON> said important representatives of each conference delegation will huddle after all 5,000 arrive in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Sunday. Those discussions are likely to remain secret. <PERSON> Ivan </PERS