<HEAD>GAO To Look at Perot's Postal Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Senate-ordered investigation may delay completion of a study by billionaire businessman <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> to find ways of saving money at the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The Senate has requested the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> to investigate terms of the deal, and directed the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to delay phase two of the contract. Postal officials, meanwhile, defended the deal Thursday and said they welcomed the investigation. `` Although we are aware that adverse statements about the contacrt are emanating from would-be competitors of Mr. <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> _ and are presenting a distorted view of this opportunity to bring his vast business experience to bear on resolving some of our problems _ we believe this contract is an appropriate step that is consistent with our ongoing efforts to prepare the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for the future,'' the agency said in a statement. The $ 500,000 deal, calling for computer specialist <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> to analyze postal operations and recommend cost-saving changes, was announced June 2. It was to last for 90 days, and be followed by a second phase in which <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> would be paid a percentage of any savings the service realized from implementing his recommendations. `` It's a beautiful arrangement for <PERSON> Perot </PERSON>, but not so pretty for the postal customers,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> will pay the costs for the first phase, then the <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> company gets a cut of the savings, if phase two is successful. Also critical of the the deal, which was not opened to competitive bids, were Sens. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grassley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION> The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> resolution called on the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> to look into the contract and report back within 45 days. It also called on the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to delay implementation of any second phase of the contract for a further 45 days to give the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> time to study the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report. Thus, if the study suggests changes in postal operations, implementation could be delayed by a month or so.
