<HEAD>South Bronx Herb Farm Bites the Dust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A greenhouse that provided herbs from the urban jungle for plates in posh restaurants has gone bankrupt after seven years. The demise of Glie Farms, known officially as <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bronx </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greenhouse </ORGANIZATION>, put more than 80 residents of the blighted <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> neighborhood out of work. `` They're no longer there. Their jobs have disappeared,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, which runs the Bathgate Industrial Park, where the herb farm once thrived. This week, the <ORGANIZATION> Sanitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> removed rows of unkempt herbs after neighbors complained of the rotting smell. But the empty greenhouses still may see future harvests. `` Something will be grown at <LOCATION> Bathgate </LOCATION> in their wake; we're optimistic,'' <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> said Thursday Glie Farms was founded in 1981, with the help of a federal grant, as a non-profit venture to provide jobs for runaway youths. After several years, it became a for-profit venture, building up a clientele of 800 restaurants and 15 supermarket chains and grossing as much as $ 250,000 a month. `` Glie Farms was a real Cinderella story,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Menge </PERSON>, the purchasing director for the Four Seasons restaurant in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. `` But that's the food business. You see so many companies come and go.'' Glie founder <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldron </PERSON> said his principal problem had been difficulty in securing a $ 1.5 million loan that he negotiated last year to start a farm in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. The company filed for bankruptcy a few weeks ago.
