<HEAD>100 Feared Buried by Turkish Landslides</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos FRA4, NY23</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mud and rock loosened by rain roared down on a mountain village and highway Thursday, burying up to 100 people, including 30 travelers stranded in a coffee house by an earlier landslide, officials said. State television said villagers reported hearing people cry out for help from beneath the ooze and rubble. `` It happened all at once after a noise that sounded like thunder. The rocks swept away everything in a second,'' said <PERSON> Turan </PERSON> <PERSON> Alemdar </PERSON>, a trucker who saw the disaster, as quoted by the <ORGANIZATION> Hurriyet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. Another witness, <PERSON> Zeki </PERSON> <PERSON> Ilha </PERSON>, was quoted as saying: `` I saw the mountain coming at me and started running away.'' Rescuers were hampered by rain. Another landslide at 8 p.m. forced a suspension of the rescue work, but caused no casualties, the television reported from <LOCATION> Catak </LOCATION> village, 500 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Ankara </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> region is known for frequent landslides, some of which are blamed on extensive cutting of forests. <PERSON> Enver </PERSON> <PERSON> Hizlan </PERSON>, the provincial governor, said only one body had been recovered. Earlier reports said three were found. Deputy Gov. <PERSON> Haydar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozgun </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> by telephone the rescue work would resume when landslide experts declared it safe. The <ORGANIZATION> Anatolia </ORGANIZATION> news agency said huge searchlights were set up. <PERSON> Safa </PERSON> <PERSON> Giray </PERSON>, federal public works minister, flew to the site. State radio said 31 people were injured by the landslide in a mountainous area of <LOCATION> Trabzon </LOCATION> province. Tons of mud and rock covered at least three houses, four stores, a restaurant and the coffee house crowded with at least 30 bus passengers stranded by an earlier landslide, the news agencies reported. A high school also was buried but no children were there because of summer vacation. Several buses and cars were on the road when the landslide hit, <ORGANIZATION> Anatolia </ORGANIZATION> reported. Television said it also clogged a river, which flooded the village, and showed footage of submerged houses. <ORGANIZATION> Anatolia </ORGANIZATION> quoted a supervising official, not identified, as saying rescuers might need two weeks to clear the debris if the rain continued. It said 40 trucks and 20 bulldozers were at the scene. Two minibuses were uncovered but no one was inside, the news reports said. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crescent </ORGANIZATION>, the Moslem equivalent of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, sent 150 tents to the area, <PERSON> Antatolia </PERSON> said. A dispatch by <ORGANIZATION> Hurriyet </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crescent </ORGANIZATION> announced over loudspeakers at scene that 300 people had been killed, causing a temporary panic. Officials at the scene and elsewhere estimated the number buried at 100 or fewer.
