<HEAD>House Keeps Family Provision in Housing Discrimination Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House on Thursday refused to kill a proposal barring discrimination in housing for families with children. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rejected on a vote of 289-116 an amendment proposed by Rep. <PERSON> Clay </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Fla </LOCATION>., that would have stripped the protection for families with children from legislation designed to strengthen the enforcement of the nation's fair housing law Under the bill, families with children under 18 could not be refused housing except in retirement communities where at least 90 percent of the tenants are 55 or older and the facilities are specifically designed for the physical or social needs of retirees. Any community renting to those 62 or older would be exempt even if it did not provide special facilities. Final action on the bill was delayed as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> recessed for the day to attend the funeral services of Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>, R-Tenn., in <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION> The bill is expected to be taken up again late next week. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders have said they would take up the bill after the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approves it, indicating that the legislation may go to the White House before the end of summer. Civil rights groups and Realtors earlier this week ended a 20-year battle by reaching a compromise to put teeth in the basic fair-housing law while still satisfying President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s concerns about constitutional guarantees. The bill would give the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> the power to bring actions on behalf of individual victims of discrimination, would ban discrimination against the disabled and would forbid limitations on renting to families with children, except in the clearly defined retirement communities. Under the compromise, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> would be required to investigate complaints of discrimination in the sale or rental of housing. And it would be authorized to lodge charges if it finds `` reasonable cause'' to believe that discrimination may have occurred. At that point, there would be an administrative proceeding unless either the plaintiff or the defendant requests a jury trial; either proceeding could lead to imposition of fines or injunctions and could be appealed to a higher court. The compromise language which gives the accused the right to a civil trial by jury was introduced by Rep. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> <PERSON> Fish </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and was passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> 401-0. The House also passed by voice vote an amendment by Rep. <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, D-Mass., which would permit the exclusion of an individual who threatens the safety of others and one by Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, R-Pa., to take away protection of the law from anyone convicted of drug The Shaw amendment would have eliminated the provisions of the bill extending protection from housing discrimination to families with children under the age of 18. It would have required the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to conduct a study on the nature and extent of housing discrimination against familes with children and report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> within three years.
