<HEAD>Strikers Assault Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Striking autoworkers demanding a 50 percent pay increase assaulted the mayor of the Slovenian city of <LOCATION> Maribor </LOCATION> on Thursday as he tried to calm them down, the official <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said the workers were angred by a report that most of the strikers from the TAM truck and military vehicle factory had returned to work, and Mayor <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuk </PERSON> tried to soothe them. `` Instead, he hardly managed to escape an assault of several angry persons,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said, without elaborating. The incident took place in the northern <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> city when strikers reportedly refused to accept a proposed 7.5 percent pay increase. A company spokesman said Thursday that about 4,000 of the employees had returned to work. <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said that 1,500 TAM workers were joined by 3,000 workers from three other plants and marched to the center of the city. It added that the workers began dispersing around noon. Sources said police blocked off one downtown street, but no arrests were made. The 5,000 employees of TAM went on strike Tuesday seeking higher wages. Several hundred workers from four other plants in the Slovenian city joined the walkout in the first such show of solidarity reported in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Politika </ORGANIZATION> said as many as 7,500 workers were involved. The strikers claim their wages threaten minimum standards of living. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is planning to reduce inflation to 90 percent this year, compared with an average 170 percent last year. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s economy, a mixture of free-market elements and Soviet-style central planning, has been growing at a sluggish rate averaging less than 1 percent annually over the past six years. The government on Saturday launched an austerity program that included substantial price increases, wage cuts of up to 30 percent and a 23.9 percent devaluation of the dinar, the national currency.
