<HEAD>House Ethics Panel to Probe Congressman in Loan Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics committee announced Thursday it is launching a formal preliminary investigation into whether Rep. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, R-Ga., violated the law or <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rules in seeking a loan that he knew was being financed by drug proceeds The panel, formally known as the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Official </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conduct </ORGANIZATION>, said it had recieved evidence `` reasonably indicating'' that <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> may have departed from acceptable standards in seeking to negotiate the $ 850,000 loan. Secretly taped conversations reported last week by the <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constitution </ORGANIZATION> showed that <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> was advised by an undercover agent that the money almost certainly came from drug trafficking, but he continued to pursue the transaction for a month. The two-term congressman was seeking to refinance a construction loan on his $ 1.2 million home in <LOCATION> Stone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, and convert it to a long-term mortgage. An aide to <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorne </PERSON>, said the ethics committee had `` done what we asked them to do.'' He said <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> had sought the investigation and was confident he would be cleared of wrongdoing. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> was on his way back to <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> for the weekend and unavailable for comment, <PERSON> Thorne </PERSON> said. A preliminary inquiry is the first step in an ethics committee investigation. If the panel finds reason to believe that the alleged violation in fact occurred, it makes a formal statement of the violation and can ultimately recommend disciplinary action. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> ultimately backed out of the deal after being told he would have to accept the cash loan in person and sign a receipt for it. `` The only reason I ca n't do that is I would then be essentially laundering y' all's money,'' <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> told an <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> undercover agent, according to the Constitution `` In other words, if <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> -LRB- </PERSON> <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON>, who has subsequently been indicted on money-laundering charges -RRB- wants to launder y' all's money, fine, but I ca n't do that, and to sign a receipt of cash would be to do that <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, at a town meeting in his congressional district last week, apologized for his behavior and asked voters to forgive him. `` I did entertain the idea, and it was wrong,'' <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> said. But he said he had no intention of resigning, and `` I hope -LRB- voters -RRB- will find it in their hearts to forgive what I have done.'' <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, who faces a tough re-election battle this fall, said he was tempted to accept the loan because of financial pressures stemming from cost overruns on the large new house he was building. But he said he backed away when he became convinced the transaction was illicit. `` When it was between myself and my maker, I made the right decision,'' he said.
