<HEAD>Sprinkel Says His Rosy Economic Views Weren't Rosy Enough</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON>, chairman of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>, took a lot of heat in the months after the stock market crash for seeing the world through rose-colored glasses and predicting strong, steady economic growth this year Many private economists had issued deeply pessimistic projections, fearing that the Oct. 19 market collapse, when investors lost $ 500 billion in a single day, would shock consumers into cutting back and topple the country into a recession. But the actual performance of the economy as measured by the gross national product _ 4.8 percent annual growth in the fourth quarter of 1987 and 3.6 percent growth in the first three months of this year _ made even the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION> estimates look too gloomy. `` Our rosy forecast was n't rosy enough. The economy is doing better than even we expected,'' a smiling, confident <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> told reporters at a White House briefing Thursday. He said the administration now expects the economy to grow 3.5 percent, year-over-year, in 1988, compared with an earlier projection of 2.9 percent. The forecast of average unemployment is moving from 5.8 percent to 5.5 percent And despite fears of inflation by stock and bond traders, he said he's holding steady on his prediction for consumer price inflation of 4.3 percent and expects only an average increase in interest rates of half a percentage point. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, responding to a reporter's question at a picture-taking session, said he's not worried about inflation either. `` All the evidence shows us that our recovery is going on and, no, there is no great threat of inflation,'' the president said. Private analysts found little fault with the administration's new growth estimate, but they said its optimistic view of inflation fails to take into account the potentially devastating effect on food prices of the drought scorching crops in the nation's `` He's certainly right about better growth ... but the rest is just pie in the sky stuff,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, an economic consultant in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> conceded the drought could have `` a significant effect on food prices,'' but said it is too soon to say how significant. `` We can not guess because I do n't know whether it's going to rain. I hope soon,'' <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> said But the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that the six-to-10-day outlook for the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> calls for more hot, dry weather. <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> noted, however, that the farm community generates only about 2 percent of the gross national product. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a government securities dealer, said, `` I think almost everyone is underestimating how devastating the drought can be to food prices.'' He noted that food makes up about one-fifth the consumer price index. `` I think the shading of the administration's estimates on inflation may involve at least some election year politics in addition to economic analysis,'' he said. `` I think what the administration is trying to do is present a picture of strong economic growth and low inflation as we come into an election.'' But <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> said, `` Our economy is not overheating, as sometimes feared.'' He said the administration bases its inflation predictions on the expectation that economic growth will slow somewhat in the remaining nine months of they year from the first-quarter pace. He said growth projections for 1989 and beyond were being revised downward slightly to offset the upward revision for 1988 and the stronger-than-expected growth experienced during 1987. For 1989, the administration expects the economy to grow 3.1 percent. `` For those of you who are always trying to figure out what we are thinking, it means we envision some decline in interest rates later this year,'' he said.
</TEXT>
