<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> said its warplanes bombed 10 Iranian oil installations Thursday in the heaviest air raids on <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s economic backbone in weeks The official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said six production installations in the <LOCATION> Ahwaz </LOCATION> oilfields in southwestern <LOCATION> Khuzestan </LOCATION> province were set on fire. Later, two installations at the <LOCATION> Bibi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hakimah </LOCATION> oilfield, 120 miles to the southeast, were bombed and set ablaze, <ORGANIZATION> INA </ORGANIZATION> said. The report was monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>. Another formation of jets hit two pumping stations at the <LOCATION> Gash </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Saran </LOCATION> field north of <PERSON> Bibi </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakimah </PERSON> at about the same time, leaving them shrouded in flames and smoke, the agency said. <ORGANIZATION> INA </ORGANIZATION> said its jet fighters flew 113 missions and its helicopter gunships 30 missions and all returned safely to their bases. There was no independent confirmation of the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> claims. But <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, also monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, reported that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> jets bombed `` a residential area and labor quarters'' in the <LOCATION> Ahvaz </LOCATION> area, killing one civilian. The agency said other unspecified areas also were bombed. But it made no mention of oil installations being hit. <ORGANIZATION> INA </ORGANIZATION> denied residential areas were hit, saying the bombing `` was confined to striking installations at oilfields and Iranian military positions.'' <ORGANIZATION> INA </ORGANIZATION> quoted a military communique as saying the raids were a message to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> that `` it has lost the war in all fields and that there is no alternative to save <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> from total deterioration but to accept peace.'' Thursday's raids were the first significant attacks on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s vital oil installations on land since early May, when fighter-bombers attacked several oil refineries and petrochemical plants The air force also has attacked several Iranian oil tankers in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> in its campaign to choke off <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s oil exports which <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> needs to pay for its war effort. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have been at war since September 1980. French-built Iraqi Mirage F-1s carried out a long-range 1,500-mile raid on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Larak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> oil terminal in the Strait of Hormuz May 14. Five tankers were set on fire. They included the world's largest vessel, the 564,739-ton <ORGANIZATION> Seawise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Giant </ORGANIZATION>, which was badly damaged. The Iraqi air offensive inflicted considerable damage on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s oil infrastructure in March and April, oil industry and diplomatic sources reported Refineries were repeatedly hit. Oil industry sources have reported that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has been forced to import unprecedented amounts of refined products, such as aviation fuel and kerosene, because its refinery production has been badly reduced. Despite the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> raids, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has maintained its oil production at around an average of 2.3 million barrels a day, with exports of around 1.4 million barrels a day, the respected Middle East Economic Survey reported. That's about the mimimum level <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> needs to maintain to earn sufficient revenue to keep its war effort going. Oil revenue accounts for some 95 percent of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s foreign exchange earnings. Oil sales earned $ 20 billion a year in 1983, but plummeted to only around $ 6 billion in 1986 when oil prices collapsed. The Iranians have suffered two major battlefield defeats in recent weeks, which along with political in-fighting in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> and economic woes, have pushed them on the defensive for the first time in several years. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s air force has been concentrating on attacking Iranian troop buildups in the past few weeks as the land war heated up, with the <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> abandoning its long-held strategy of static defense to go on the offensive for the first time in six years.
