<HEAD>High-Rise Apartments Planned for Black Township</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A company said Thursday it plans to build the first high-rise apartment complex in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, the vast black township where tens of thousands of people live in shacks because of a housing shortage. The project envisions 40,000 people would be able to live in 7,000 to 8,000 apartments in buildings up to 25 stories. Two dozen schools will be built in six three-story buildings nearby, according to the $ 230 million plan by the non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>. The highest building in <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>, where an estimated 2.5 million people live on 40 square miles of low hills, is now a 10-story nurses' dormitory. Aside from a few two-story houses in higher-income neighborhoods, Sowetans live on small lots in one-story houses. Many have outside toilets and no bathrooms. Most homes now have running water and electricity, but squatters, relatives and friends of householders live by the thousands in shacks, sheds and garages. There are relatively few apartment buildings for blacks anywhere in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The proposed Soweto complex would house 40,000 people where two hostels previously accommodated 4,000. The non-profit foundation said a studio apartment in the new complex would be sold rather than rented and would cost about $ 6,000. It said that compared to an average $ 6,500 for a serviced plot of land without a house in a township. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s apartheid laws require blacks to live in segregated townships, most of them relatively far from urban centers where they work. Under apartheid, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs and have separate schools and health services. Anti-apartheid activists accuse of the government of restricting the available land for black housing to control the numbers of blacks in urban areas. One result has been massive squatter camps. The government recently announced a plan to add vacant land to the black townships around <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> for more black housing. One proposed community north of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> may be designated as an area where people of any race could live.
