<HEAD>Drought Takes Toll on Abandoned Baby Sparrow Hawks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Heat-Drought, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A family is feeding worms to a nestful of baby sparrow hawks after the birds' parents apparently abandoned them to search for water and food amid the lingering drought. Five baby American kestrels, a type of small falcon commonly known as a sparrow hawk, plopped down at the picnic table of <PERSON> June </PERSON> <PERSON> Shawver </PERSON>'s home in this community Monday. Family members have been giving worms to the brown-speckled birds, which are members of a federally protected species. `` Sunday, I saw a bird out my window that I thought was an owl,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Shawver </PERSON>. She now believes the bird was probably the adult bird just as it was abandoning the nest. The next day, she found the babies, who are about 6 inches long and will grow to up to 12 inches. The birds happily dined on worms that the family had gathered to feed a pet turtle, she said. `` They were gobbling them up like crazy,'' Ms. <PERSON> Shawver </PERSON> said. Because the kestrels, like all birds of prey, are protected by federal law, Ms. <PERSON> Shawver </PERSON> notified State Game Protector <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Duckworth </PERSON>. <PERSON> Duckworth </PERSON> said it was not normal for parent birds to leave a nest like that. `` More than likely it was the lack of water and insects that prompted the birds to abandon the nest,'' <PERSON> Duckworth </PERSON> said. `` There was not enough food for the parents to survive, so they left.'' While it is illegal to possess the kestrels, dead or alive, the Shawvers will be allowed to feed the baby birds so long as they are not confined in any way, <PERSON> Duckworth </PERSON> said. The birds are gradually getting adult feathers, Ms. <PERSON> Shawver </PERSON> said. `` You can see them changing every day,'' she said. `` The female is the most aggressive. She is bigger than the rest. She seems to stand up by herself a lot.''
