il system <PERSON> Moe </PERSON> <PERSON> Biller </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, called plans by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> to expand its shipment of toxic materials through the postal system `` bizarre'' and a `` devious scheme'' that should be rejected. He said that at the very least the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> should require a permit to ship toxic specimens `` and should require advance notice before it is presented for acceptance into the mailstream.'' Eighteen members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> sent a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> earlier this month expressing their concerns about the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s plan to expand the shipment of toxins by registered mail from research centers around the country to a proposed testing center at the Dugway Proving Grounds in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. Such shipments, said Rep. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelosi </PERSON>, D-Calif., `` will expose postal workers and the general public to an unacceptable health risk. She said the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> has gone `` to great lengths'' to describe the safety precautions being taken at the proposed laboratory but shows a lack of concern with shipping safeguards. Thousands of toxins and disease agents are shipped through the postal service by private laboratories as well as the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>, witnesses said. While the shipments require strict packaging, in some cases up to five layers of packing, there still are spills, witnesses said. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Miss </PERSON>, a Pos