llor </PERSON>'s appearance before the press club no differently than it handled talks by others. The nonprofit radio network said it has distributed tapes of those events to the public through its cassette catalog since 1979 and has more than 130 titles. <ORGANIZATION> Spoken </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which produces and distributes some cassettes for <ORGANIZATION> NPR </ORGANIZATION>, was included in the settlement. Officials at Spoken Arts were out of the office and not available for comment. <ORGANIZATION> NPR </ORGANIZATION> said it believes <PERSON> Keillor </PERSON>'s book publicist was aware when he arranged the appearance that cassettes would be distributed and that <PERSON> Keillor </PERSON> also was aware of the arrangements. `` NPR thinks it is important to preserve its right to distribute programs and cassettes of press club appearances as part of its service to the listening public,'' the radio network said. <PERSON> Keiller </PERSON>'s nationally broadcast variety show, `` A Prairie Home Companion,'' which was produced by <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> and distributed by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>, was discontinued a year ago.
