<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Heat Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> told President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Thursday that it is too early for emergency relief measures to deal with effects of the drought, a White House spokesman reported. `` Despite the serious potential effects of the drought, the secretary said rainfall in the next two weeks would alleviate much of the potential damage,'' Deputy Press Secretary <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said. Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, however, said in a separate statement, `` If conditions continue to deteriorate, money that has been saved in this year's farm programs will be redirected to farm families as disaster relief for the rural economy.'' Rising crop prices are expected to reduce the direct subsidies that would have to be paid to farmers this year, saving an unspecified amount of federal money. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> also reported that the <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drought </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is establishing a toll-free telephone number to answer questions about federal services available to citizens in drought-stricken areas. The hotline begins operation Friday and will operated from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. EDT on weekdays and from 9 a.m. to 1 p.m. EDT on Saturdays. The number is 1-800-541-3375. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> briefed the president and vice president and then the Cabinet in separate meetings He said <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> showed <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> a map that demonstrated the worsening condition of the drought in many areas of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` The secretary said that in discussions he has had with congressmen and senators, farm groups and governors, there was agreement that it is too early for emergency relief measures,'' the White House spokesman said. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> also reported that the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and other agencies have taken some steps to help, such as allowing haying and grazing on conservation reserves. The spokesman quoted <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as saying after the meeting, `` Our No. 1 worry right now is the effects of the drought on the farmers and their families and making certain they receive any help we can provide.''
