<HEAD>Pope Begins Visit to Austria Recalling `Cruel Tyranny' of Nazism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with private meeting of Waldheim
and pope; pope retires for night; CLARIFIES that pope addressed
Waldheim along with government and church leaders in ceremonial
hall. EDITS to TRIM. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VIE3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> recalled the evils of Nazism during a meeting Thursday with President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, who has been accused of being involved in war crimes while serving in <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s army. Foreign diplomats did not attend a speech by the pope to church and government officials including <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, who has been virtually ostracized internationally because of his wartime past. But diplomats warmly greeted the pope at a reception afterwards. `` In this year of 1988, I should like to particularly recall the great trials and cruel tyranny which <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, along with other nations, had to suffer in the not too distant past,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said in his speech, at the beginning of a five-day visit to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, his second since becoming pope in 1978. `` Amongst the many who were persecuted for religious, racial and political reasons were large numbers of Catholics _ priests, members of religious orders and lay people,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said in an ornate ceremonial hall of the Hofburg Palace. About 80 people, including government officials and church leaders, attended the gathering. The pope delivered his address in German. This year is the 50th anniversary of the `` Anschluss,'' when <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> annexed his native country in 1938. The event, coupled with a war record that continues to dog <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, has inspired controversy and soul-searching. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> has repeatedly denied involvement in war crimes. In his own greeting, <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> thanked the pontiff for receiving him at the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> in June 1987 _ a meeting that drew a bitter response from Jewish leaders because of questions about the president's war service. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> said at the time that <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> was receiving the office, not the man. <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON> has said of the pope's trip to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>: `` This is not a political visit, it is a pastoral visit. He was invited by the bishops.'' <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> and his family later posed for pictures with the pontiff at the <LOCATION> Hofburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palace </LOCATION>. Then the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> met privately with <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> for about five minutes, but <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON> declined to say what the two men talked about. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> did not attend a reception afterwards where the envoys greeted the pope, according to a pool report distributed to journalists. The pope then retired for the night at the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> archbishop's residence. Protests coincided with the pope's arrival. Earlier Thursday, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said an evening Mass at St. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON>'s Cathedral. As he was about to start, American Jews displayed banners at the windows of a hotel across the square from the cathedral. The banners said `` Nazi Waldheim'' and `` Do n't Meet <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>.'' Police ordered the banners removed. Several hours before <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> arrived, Rabbi <PERSON> Avi </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Riverdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and five other American Jews demonstrated outside <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s office. `` Do not embrace <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, no!'' <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> told a small crowd attracted to the demonstration. The other five members of the group were dressed in black-and-white striped uniforms similar to those of concentration camp inmates. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Elan </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, issued a statement saying: `` The pope's meeting with his flock in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> is not what troubles the Jewish community. It is the deliberate inclusion of meetings with <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> on his itinerary.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> will make about 20 appearances in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, 85 percent of whose 7.5 million people are <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>. He visited the country for three days in 1983. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, smiling and wearing a blue suit, was the first person to greet the white-robed pontiff as he stepped off the special <ORGANIZATION> Alitalia </ORGANIZATION> jetliner at <LOCATION> Schwechat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. The pope mentioned several places he will visit, including <LOCATION> Mauthausen </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> concentration camp where 110,000 prisoners died. `` Let us, when we meet, bring before God not only the great and burdensome legacy of the past but also the joys and sorrows of the present,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said, speaking in German. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> also denounced `` intolerance, intransigence and hate among nations, religions and classes,'' but made no direct reference to the dispute over his past. Most Western leaders shun <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, who was <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general for 10 years, because of allegations of complicity in Nazi atrocities. The charges arose during the election campaign two years ago. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> denies wrongdoing but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has barred him from the country, saying it has evidence he was involved in deporting civilians while serving as a German army officer in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> during World War II. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, on the 38th foreign pilgrimage of his papacy, also will meet with representatives of <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s small Jewish community and address Roman Catholics from neighboring communist countries.
