<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted Thursday to give victims of rape or incest the right to federally funded abortions. The panel voted 15-14 to defeat a motion to delete the provision, which had been added earlier this week by a subcommittee to the fiscal 1989 spending bill for the departments of health and human services, labor and education. The Office of Management and Budget, in a letter to committee members, said presidential advisers would recommend a veto of the $ 139 billion bill if it includes the abortion provision. The sponsor of the motion, Sen. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., argued before the committee that `` denying Medicaid funds to poor women for what is legal in this country makes no sense. The annual spending bill usually contains a provision saying abortions can only be paid for under the federal-state Medicaid program when the woman's life would be endangered by carrying the fetus to term. The version approved by the committee would return the law to its status before 1980. The same provision was added in 1986 in committee, but removed on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor. The 1989 spending bill is expected to reach the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor next month. <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> called the new abortion provision a Medicaid expansion that `` diverges from longstanding policy on this issue.'' <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> called the <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> letter `` a waste of power'' that diverts attention from the needs of the nation into `` narrow philosophical issues.''
