Canada </LOCATION> would not be allowed to return. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> retaliated Wednesday by expelling two Canadian diplomats and barring re-entry for three others, alleging espionage. A statement Thursday from Canadian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said the espionage allegations against the Canadian diplomats in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> are `` totally without justification.'' It said the latest expulsions follow `` Soviet espionage activities in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> which have obliged the Canadian government to expel the Soviet officials.'' The statement gave no details of the alleged spying by <PERSON> Roublev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kashtanov </PERSON>, but <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s press secretary <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazer </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> they were involved in `` unacceptable activities,'' the usual euphemism for spying. <PERSON> Frazer </PERSON> said <PERSON> Roublev </PERSON> has been in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> since May 1985, while <PERSON> Kashtanov </PERSON> served in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> from February 1981 to August 1985. Asked why they had not been expelled earlier, <PERSON> Frazer </PERSON> said: `` We think our response is appropriate in the circumstances.'' He said the Soviet ambassador was called in Thursday and informed of the latest action. He was also told that <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> was willing to `` put the matter behind us'' if <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> did likewise, <PERSON> Frazer </PERSON> said. The last wave of mass expulsions was in 1978 when 13 Soviet diplomats were expelled for trying to recruit a <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mounted </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> intelligence officer as a double agent. The Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting 