<SECOND>AM-Veterans Records Found,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Millions Of Duplicate Records Found That Could Reopen Disability
Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Veterans Administration announced Thursday the discovery of 10 million military medical records that duplicate some lost in a devastating 1973 fire, and said it will review disability claims that were rejected because of the lost files. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Turnage </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> administrator, said the agency just became aware of the records last week and it was too early to tell how many people would be affected. But he called the development `` very important.'' `` It opens up new vistas for us. It means that these people who before had difficulty establishing a basis for their disability compensation, or the degree of it, ... it means we can have another chance to look at it and, in effect, may come up with a different result,'' <PERSON> Turnage </PERSON> said. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sommer </PERSON>, the director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, whose office helps veterans with their disability claims, said the development potentially could affect thousands of former military personnel. `` We've handled many cases where there were no records because of the fire and it's very difficult to develop additional evidence on which to try to get these claims allowed,'' he said in an interview. `` You'd be amazed at the number of people, World War II veterans in particular, who waited until they retired to file a claim with the VA, and then found the records had been destroyed,'' <PERSON> Sommer </PERSON> said. `` Many of them felt they just did n't want to take anything from the government ... Then, as they aged, they decided to file a claim and discovered their records had been burned.'' Eighteen million military personnel records were destroyed or seriously damaged in the July 12, 1973 fire at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Personnel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Record </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. The lost records were from the years 1912 through 1959 for <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> personnel, and 1947 through 1963 for <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> personnel with the surnames of <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON> and through the letter Z. The duplicate records cover the years 1942 to 1945 and 1950 to 1954, so will primarily affect veterans of World War II and the Korean War. The records were collected by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a private research organization, during the 1950s as part of its analysis of Army hospital records. A researcher at the council came across the records and notified the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Brett </PERSON>, an archives spokeswoman. Ms. <PERSON> Brett </PERSON> said the records are on computer magnetic tapes created by the council from admissions punch cards prepared by the office of the surgeon general. She said the archives paid the council $ 8,662 for the tapes and will reformat them for cross-referencing against other files. The records were not listed by the military officer's name, but included the officer's serial number, grade and rank, age, date and place of admission as well as disease and diagnosis, Ms. <PERSON> Brett </PERSON> said. Veterans applying for monthly disability benefits as a result of injury or illness suffered while on active duty must have some verification of their claim. <PERSON> Turnage </PERSON> said he did not have figures on how many disability claims had been denied as a result of the lost records. There were 3.5 million files that turned up for the year 1944 alone, <PERSON> Turnage </PERSON> said, covering about 2.4 million people. For 1945, 2 million files were discovered, covering about 1.4 million people. But officials cautioned against the notion that millions of veterans would be affected by the discovery. <PERSON> R.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s chief benefits director, said that most of the veterans who made disability claims did so during their initial years after service and likely would have filed claims before 1973 Those most likely to be affected by the discovery of the records include people with an injury suffered during active duty which was aggravated over the years, such as a back or heart ailment, <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> said it would immediately begin reviewing disability claims rejected because of the lost records. The agency said it also expected many veterans would come forward seeking information about their claims. It said those people should contact their VA regional offices.
