. Its gilded central stupa, or tower, soars 325 feet above a temple base adorned with more than five tons of gold. Burmese are almost fanatically devoted to the shrine, which legend says was founded 2,500 years ago. It has survived wars, earthquakes and the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> occupation, during which it was a center for anti-colonial nationalists. Residents reached by telephone in <LOCATION> Mandalay </LOCATION>, about 380 miles north of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>, said classes were suspended at <ORGANIZATION> Mandalay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. The action appeared to be precautionary, since no trouble was reported. Similar reports from <PERSON> Pegu </PERSON> said an overnight curfew was imposed Wednesday after students and other rioters destroyed or heavily damaged government buildings, vehicles and cooperative stores. Pegu was the seat of several ancient kingdoms. Western analysts say restrictions on individual freedoms and poor economic conditions are spurring the protest. Although <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> is rich in resources and has an educated populace, its per capita annual income of less than $ 200 puts it among the poorest nations. Ne Win's `` Burmese Way to Socialism'' mixes military control, socialism and few dealings with the outside world. Most merchants in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>'s sprawling market districts closed their shops at noon Thursday for fear of looting if violence resumed. Some government employees went home before normal closing hours. Attendance was minimal at high schools and the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, the only center of higher learning still open in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. Teachers were told to continue classes regardless of the attendance level. No major incidents have been reported since the curfew took effect Tuesday. A few street vendors and drivers of taxis and rickshaws have been arrested for going out before 6 a.m., but were reported freed after warnings. The latest trouble began Tuesday when 5,000 students and other protesters in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> fought police with stones. Students at several institutions demonstrated peacefully last week for legalization of student unions and release of detained comradesd. The government closed the school and the government responded with violence. Trouble began last October when the government declared much of the currency in circulation to be invalid and did not offer compensation. On March 18, after several days of unrest, police and soldiers quickly crushed a rampage in downtown <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> by students and other protesters. A government panel announced only two deaths and said 625 people were arrested, but diplomatic sources told reporters in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, as many as 100 people have been killed since October. Many of those arrested have been released.
