 A federal agency is investigating an arson fire at a <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> warehouse owned by the same company whose <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> plant was ravaged by fire over the weekend, routing 25,000 people from their homes. While the federal <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alcohol </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Firearms </ORGANIZATION> was looking into the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> warehouse fire Thursday, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> investigators were on their way to <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> to take a look at the burned-out plant, <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> fire department spokesman <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> <PERSON> Placanico </PERSON> said. `` We'll probably go down there, too,'' <PERSON> Placanico </PERSON> said. Firefighters in protective suits continued carting barrels of chloride out of the remains of the 18th-century mill Thursday as ambulances stood by in case pockets of fumes overwhelmed the workers. The <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> plant burned for four days, spewing a three-mile-long gas cloud across the city of 170,000 and forced thousands out of the neighborhood before firefighters controlled the last of several fires Monday. The first fire apparently was sparked by rainwater that fell through a window of the <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> plant and mixed with chloride tablets that the plant makes for swimming pools, causing a violent reaction. The later fires are under investigation. A June 10 fire at a <ORGANIZATION> Weatherking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> warehouse in <LOCATION> Doraville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, owned by the same company, also appears to be accidental, sa