aries of <ORGANIZATION> Aquafab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, a pool supply firm owned by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perreira </PERSON> of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Boca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Raton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Coventry </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, according to records filed with secretaries of state in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> has released records showing that since April 1986, state officials have investigated a series of incidents at the plant, including charges that the firm was illegally dumping chlorine chemicals in a nearby pond. An attorney for the company has said the owners will have no comment until the damage from the fire has been assessed.
