<HEAD>Governors Of Parched States Hear Agriculture Secretary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Heat, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said Thursday federal programs will provide relief for drought-stricken farmers, but governors meeting in emergency session questioned whether those methods were adequate. During a brief appearance before the 10 governors who gathered for the day-long conference, <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> promised the federal government `` will do what is needed to minimize the severity of the damage.'' But the agriculture secretary also reminded the gathering that there were several existing aid programs already in place, and he stressed repeatedly that the extent of the damage from the drought was yet to be determined. But Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, speaking at a closing news conference, said farmers in several states already had lost much of their cash crops and others have sold off entire livestock herds for lack of feed grain. `` Where I think he -LRB- <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> -RRB- is wrong is in the wheat area,'' said Sinner. `` That damage is done and it is very, very severe. In the livestock feed area, that damage is done and it's going to grow.'' Sinner also said government programs must be made flexible enough to ensure that farmers hurt by the current drought are n't disqualified from participating in crop-insurance and disaster-loan program because of `` technicalities. `` I'm afraid we're going to lose some farmers,'' he said, `` and we've lost enough already in my state.'' That message echoed throughout the day. `` Welcome to the heart of the droughtland,'' Illinois Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said in opening the conference. `` We used to be known as the heart of the heartland. Now we are both.'' In his speech, <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> noted that 1,200 counties in 30 states already have been granted permission for grazing livestock or making hay on government-rented land normally set aside for conservation or crop-reduction plans. He also pointed out that task forces already have been set up within the administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to study the consequences of the drought. The federal government's crop-insurance and disaster-loan programs could serve large number of farmers once the extent of the damage from the drought becomes clear, he said. `` The situation is still fluid. ... We'll need a little bit of time to learn what the losses are,'' he said. Before he left the conference, <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said he would meet with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Friday morning to update him on the drought situation. But several governors suggested the situation in their states already demands a more-specific response from the federal goverment _ even if they had different ideas on what the response should be. Illinois' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said the barge traffic along the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> so crucial to agricultural states like <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> was paralyzed because of low water levels, and proposed he <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> seek permission to divert water from <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> to solve the problem. That proposal, however, was disputed by <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. `` It might turn out to be more disastrous over the long term than the immediate salvation it provides,'' said the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> governor. `` It's an idea we should explore. I'm just saying we should not go quickly, though.'' <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said restoring last year's 50-cent price cut on federal dairy support programs and blocking a second cut next January `` would do more for <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> farmers than anything but rain.'' Given the differing needs of the states represented, <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> was asked how they would reach agreement on priorities. `` That's difficult,'' he said, `` any time you deal with agricultural issues, everybody has a different agenda. ... But this issue is crucial enough for us to find a common ground.'' Attending the day-long meeting, besides <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON> and both <PERSON> Thompsons </PERSON>, were the governors of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebaska </LOCATION>.
