<FIRST>u a TwoCaliforniaCompaniesPushingSeedlessProducontheSenatefloor.
    06-23 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>Two California Companies Pushing Seedless Product</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some watermelons no longer rate as seedy characters. Two <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> companies, <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Petoseed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, are marketing seedless watermelons, which are showing up in supermarkets across the nation for the first time. Sun World has launched a national marketing effort for its seedless watermelons, while Petoseed has provided several growers with seeds and is promoting hybrid seedless varieties the company developed. The need to spit out the seeds to the juicy fruit has long been the pits, but the idea of ending such expectorating has been around a while, too. `` The process by which it is produced was developed in the late 1930s,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Marguleas </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>'s merchandising manager. Seedless watermelons did n't catch on then because they were `` very difficult to grow, very expensive to farm, and production of seed for seedless watermelons was produced on a very limited basis,'' he added. Dr. <PERSON> O.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Eigsti </PERSON> continued work on developing seedless watermelons in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. He had no commercial success until recent years when his <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seedless </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> formed a joint venture to have <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> promote and distribute them. Petoseed began a breeding program in 1976 to develop seedless watermelons for sale in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON>, the company's product marketing coordinator The Japanese have eaten seedless watermelons produced by their own farmers for more than two decades, he noted. Petoseed has developed three seedless varieties, which have been planted on about 600 acres this year. Sun World, which markets about 75 California-grown fruits and vegetables, test-marketed seedless watermelons grown on 180 acres last year, then expanded production to 2,000 acres this season, <PERSON> Marguleas </PERSON> said. Regular watermelons with seeds were grown on more than 15,000 acres of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> farm land in 1986, the last year for which state statistics have been compiled. The crop that year totaled 186,000 tons valued at $ 27.7 million. Sun World seedless watermelons will be available in most major markets during the summer, said <PERSON> Marguleas </PERSON>, who was in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> last week promoting the product to food editors. `` Not only gone are those annoying black seeds, consumers also found the flavor sweeter and crunchier than the average watermelon,'' <PERSON> Marguleas </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Buck </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> seedless watermelons will carry `` a sticker on the side that says they are seedless with a disclaimer that says they may contain an occasional seed.'' Consumers will find a couple of other things different in comparing seedless varieties with regular watermelons. Both Marguleas and <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON> said seedless watermelons could cost two or three times as much as seeded watermelons, which now range from 9 to 19 cents a pound. <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON> said the difficulty in growing seedless watermelons and the extra cost will limit their popularity to about 15 percent of the market. `` I do n't see it as taking over the watermelon market,'' he said. `` I see it as a specialty item.
</TEXT>
