<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> left Thursday for a week-long visit to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> during which he said he would present <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials with plans for the future of the Israeli-occupied lands. <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said he would meet with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and other top <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials but described his trip as a `` regular visit.'' Israeli officials did not disclose <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>'s itinerary for security reasons. `` I will take an opportunity before the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> elections to thank a sympathetic, supportive administration, and particularly President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> who has done so much for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s security,'' <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said before departing from <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Ben </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gurion </LOCATION> airport. The defense minister said he planned to discuss with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> situation and the Arab uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, which has claimed the lives of 211 Palestinians and four Israelis since it began last Dec. 8. `` I'm bringing them some plans for the future,'' <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said without elaborating. <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>'s visit comes amidst <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> criticism of Israeli policies in the occupied territories. The latest criticism came Thursday, when <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> accused <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> of violating Palestinian human rights. Speaking at <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ilan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> called on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to stop deportations, administrative detentions, house demolitions and other measures of what he termed collective punishment. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has deported 21 Palestinians since the uprising began. As of June 9, at least 2,500 Palestinians have been served with administrative detention orders, a measure allowing the army to hold a suspect in jail for a period of up to six months without trial. In apparent response to <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON>'s criticism, <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> revealed plans to release some Palestinian detainees. He said between 50 and 80 prisoners are beingh released every day. `` If a village or a family have shown good behavior, we are going to release some detainees from the area,'' <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said. `` We want to use the carrot as well, not only the stick.''
