<HEAD>Pregnant Woman Hurt By Bomb Loses One Twin In Emergency Delivery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman pregnant with twins underwent an emergency Caesarian section Thursday after being injured in a bomb blast. One of the babies died and the other was in critical condition, officials said. The 20-year-old mother, <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Ebrahim </PERSON>, was reported in serious condition at <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. The babies were delivered seven weeks prematurely. Mrs. <PERSON> Ebrahim </PERSON>, her husband, and their 2-year-old daughter were among 10 people injured Wednesday when a limpet mine exploded at a video game arcade in downtown <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. There have been more than 20 bombings in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> this year, killing eight people and injuring 59. The government has blamed the attacks on the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement. The <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>, which is fighting the government because of its policy of apartheid, has not claimed responsibility for specific attacks in recent months but has said it seeks to intensify its guerrilla operations. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
