Savain </PERSON> also is detained. Radio Haiti-Inter said Thursday that <PERSON> Benodin </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Mireille </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> party officials <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frantz </PERSON> <PERSON> Jean-Louis </PERSON> also hold <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship and are under detention. On Thursday, armed soldiers stood guard outside the sacked headquarters of <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rally </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The sidewalk was littered with desks, campaign posters and broken glass. `` We saw him -LRB- <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> -RRB- on television shaking his Uzi -LRB- machinegun -RRB-,'' said a 21-year-old maid, speaking on condition her name not be used. `` People who do n't understand are n't afraid. People who do understand are.'' <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> headed a junta that governed <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> for two years after dictator <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> fled to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> on Feb. 7, 1986. <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> turned over power last Feb. 7 to <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON>, who won presidential elections in January with the army's help. <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> dismissed <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> as military commander June 17 in a dispute over transfers of army officers and put him under house arrest. Soldiers freed <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> Sunday night, captured the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palace </ORGANIZATION> and sent <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> into exile in the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, which shares the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> island of Hispaniola with <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON> said he would travel to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> Friday and leave for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> over the weekend. Journalists at Haitian radio stations say they fear a media crackdown and will think twice before reporting controversial news. Haitians still remember the bloody reprisals of last summer, when soldiers opened fire on unarmed anti-government demonstrators and bystanders, killing more than 100 people. Thugs killed at least 34 people during presidential elections last Nov. 29, which were aborted to stop the violence. `` <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> has shown us what he can do, so what will happen is no mystery,'' said <PERSON> Lucille </PERSON>, a hairdresser who spoke on condition she not be fully identified. Businessmen fear the army's latest takeover will provoke more capital flight and disinvestment by foreign assembly plants, which employ more than 40,000 Haitians. `` I think things can only get worse now,'' said a wholesale businessman who imports canned goods, dried fish and other foodstuffs. `` For two years he -LRB- <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> -RRB- did n't do any good for the country. I think people have lost all hope of betterment. There is no more democracy, no more progress, no more Constitution.''
