<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A black man who tried to aid a white woman on a <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> street early Thursday was assaulted by at least three white men, who screamed racial slurs as they pummelled him with sticks and their fists, police said. It was the second racial attack in the city in two days. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Frederique </PERSON>, 25, was treated for cuts and bruises at a hospital, and one of his alleged assailants was later arrested. At least two other men were being sought. <PERSON> Frederique </PERSON>, reached by telephone at his home, refused to comment on the incident. It occurred one day after a black man walking home from work on <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> was attacked by six white men. He was defended by two white men at a pizzeria where he sought aid. Investigators said <PERSON> Frederique </PERSON> was riding his bike home from visiting his girlfriend at 2:30 a.m. when he saw a white woman arguing with a white man in front of a bar in <LOCATION> Astoria </LOCATION>. The white man walked away and <PERSON> Frederique </PERSON> approached the white woman. `` Basically, he was offering her assistance,'' said Capt. <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> of the police Bias Unit. Two white men standing across the street threw a bottle at the black man, began screaming racial slurs at Frederique and yelled `` you do n't belong here,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. The men began pushing and shoving <PERSON> Frederique </PERSON>, until he remounted his bike to escape. The men, and at least one other companion, followed <PERSON> Frederique </PERSON> in a car and tried to run him off the road. They caught up with him, left their car and began beating the bicyclist with sticks and their fists. <PERSON> Frederique </PERSON> abandoned his bike, and picked up a garbage can to defend himself, the captain said. The victim escaped his assailants and ran about two blocks to a gasoline station, where the attendant called police. Officers took <PERSON> Frederique </PERSON> through the neighborhood and he was able to identify one of his alleged assailants. <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Tellier </PERSON>, 29, was charged with second-degree assault and aggravated harassment, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. In Wednesday's incident on <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the six alleged assailants were arrested and charged with assault. Reports of bias incidents have decreased in the borough of <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> in 1988, compared to 1987, but are on the rise citywide, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. There were 69 bias incidents reported in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> from January 1988 to May 31, 1988, down from 85 such incidents during the same period in 1987. However, as of May 31 of this year, 243 bias incidents were reported in the five boroughs, an increase over the 217 incidents reported in 1987.
