<DATELINE>BARTLESVILLE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Someone with a sense of fowl play keeps stealing the city's duck crossing signs, so street officials have decided to sell the yello caution signs to pay the bills. The duck silhouette on a diamond-shaped sign is supposed to warn motorists to watch for ducks crossing the street near a neighborhood park pond. Since first installing the caution signs about two years ago, the city has put up about 20 of the signs. All have disappeared. At $ 75 apiece, the street department is out $ 1,500 for the signs, said <PERSON> Garold </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> of the town's streets department. He said officials figure the missing signs have become wall hangings in dormitories and bedrooms. Officials decided last week they would bow to market demand and offer the signs for sale at $ 28 to $ 35 apiece. `` I do n't know if it will do any good but we thought we would try to sell them,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. `` We are not here to make a profit. The people in the area want the ducks protected.''
