<FIRST>a i PM-Britain-GreenFight Adv30   06-23 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Green Fight, Adv 30,0754</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs June 30 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>British Countrysiders Fighting Development</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPENCERS WOOD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> worries that the rolling green countryside of <LOCATION> Spencers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wood </LOCATION> is endangered, that throngs from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> 35 miles to the east will pour into tracts of houses where now there are trees and meadows. He heads a group of 450 local residents opposing the suburbanization of their countryside in <LOCATION> Spencers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wood </LOCATION> and all of <LOCATION> Berkshire </LOCATION> <LOCATION> county </LOCATION> where tiny villages are designated by the government as the sites for thousands of new homes for people overflowing from crowded <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The battle of <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> is a test case in a political controversy brewing across southern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belt </ORGANIZATION>, a ring of protected land around <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, has put housing-development pressure on more outlying rural areas like Spencers Wood. `` Once the atmosphere goes, it's no longer country living, so to speak,'' said <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> as he surveyed smokestacks and a sea of rowhouses on one side of the highway running through the area and the green land on the other. The issue touches sensitive political nerves. Critics, even in Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, say that by funneling development to the wealthy southern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, the government is ignoring the economically ailing north and widening national divisions. Environment Minister <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> and developers argue that houses must be built where they are needed, and that's in the south. They maintain that denying free-market forces, a cornerstone of Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s policies, would dampen southern growth. `` This issue is potentially as explosive for the <ORGANIZATION> Tories </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Conservatives -RRB- as any that has caused rumblings of discontent within their ranks during the past decade,'' commented the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. At the heart of the controversy is the <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belt </ORGANIZATION>, the 1.2 million acres set aside 50 years ago around <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to keep the city from sprawling to the sea, give it a `` green lung,'' and preserve the city's character. Belts around other cities followed and <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belts </ORGANIZATION> now cover 14 percent of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. As part of her goal of transforming <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> into `` a property-owning democracy,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> wants everyone to have the chance to buy a home. But she could not touch the Green Belts without alienating large numbers of voters in the south, her electoral heartland. The planned Channel Tunnel linking southern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the growth of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> as a financial capital have sent real estate prices soaring and added greater burdens on hospitals and other services. Opponents like <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> say it's fine to protect the Green Belts, but unfair to make the countryside pay the price. They say inner cities should be revitalized with new housing. `` We think it's bad management for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s inner cities to be depopulating and green fields to be built over,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiggin </PERSON>, a lawmaker who opposes his <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s development policy. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bate </PERSON>, senior planner for the 60-year-old Council for the Protection of Rural <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> -LRB- CPRE -RRB-, says: `` If we continue to have major housebuilding and investment in the southeast and not in other parts of the country, the problem of two nations under one government is going to become even greater than it already is.'' <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> argues that city dwellers `` need parks and green spaces and gardens, too, and resent the implication that all development can just be dumped in their backyard.'' The controversy heated up in February after <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> increased estimates of southeast housing needs from 460,000 homes to a possible 610,000 by the year 2000. `` We've taken -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- as a test case because it is the county under the greatest pressure,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CPRE </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Bate </PERSON> said in an interview. `` It's an area which has seen a doubling of its housing stock in the last 30 years, where villages have already been absorbed into main towns.'' A right-wing think tank, the <ORGANIZATION> Adam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, has suggested reviving <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belt </ORGANIZATION> land that was once used for industry and fell derelict after the conservation area was introduced. It says up to 40 percent of the belt consists of such `` brown'' patches and proposes letting developers in provided they also make other spoiled areas `` green'' again. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> and his neighbors, in the meantime, worry about what they will lose. Small developments already peek from behind the trees and old homes of their region. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> already has encroached.
</TEXT>
