<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Tales of the Black-eyed Peas, the Jackass and the King</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Vietnam Papers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE ESPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUITLAND, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Amid documents recording the battles, decisions and agony of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, the war's lighter and slighter moments were also dutifully noted in the 12 million pages of Army papers recently opened to the public at the National Archives. Here is a sampling.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 An infantry captain inquiring about the availability of black-eyed peas was told by headquarters that this Southern specialty was not on the Army's master menu. How could that be, he asked, since one unit he knew of had several pallets of peas and its supply officer had promised the division general, `` Yes, general, the troops will have black-eyed peas for New Year's day.'' Besides, the captain said, the black-eyed peas matter, as it was termed in the papers, was of interest to the president of the black-eyed pea industry as well as to Gen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Westmoreland </PERSON>, the commander of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and a <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> native. The captain was told that the peas in question were either surplus from the commissary store or had been mistakenly unloaded in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. The military log dated Jan. 2, 1968, reporting this exchange, had this final entry: ACTION TAKEN None.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Speaking of <LOCATION> Westmoreland </LOCATION>, when the king of <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> learned the general was planning a visit in May 1968, he invited the general over to talk since Thai troops were serving with the allied forces in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. But Mrs. <PERSON> Westmoreland </PERSON>, who was accompanying her husband, was excluded. As the charge d'affaires of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> explained in this cable to <LOCATION> Westmoreland </LOCATION>: `` We have learned from the king's chief aide-de-camp that his majesty is looking forward to a rather lengthy serious discussion of the war with you, and -LRB- his aide -RRB- expressed the view that ` this might be tiresome for the ladies.' Since I take this to be a clear indication of the king's preference for a serious stag talk, I am inclined to let it rest that way. Accordingly ... we have planned the itinerary with this in view.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 When Lt. Col. <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, an Army dentist stationed in <LOCATION> Saigon </LOCATION>, was asked if he had any equipment problems, he was blunt: `` I had some jackass come over from the States. The clinic was a hootch, bamboo sides, canvas, too. ... He came in and looked at the X-ray machine and he told me I could not use it because we did not have a lead screen. `` I told him, ` You see my name.' I had my name on my uniform and I said, ` I set that X-ray machine up. ... I get people sent in here from all over the country to get an X-ray taken. I am going to continue using it and you can put that in your report.' ... I never heard any further.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
