<FIRST>s i BC-Conference-PartyHistory Adv26   06-23 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Conference-Party History, Adv 26,0312</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Conference First Since 1941</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Soviet Conference,b0639-b0640</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communist Party Conference opening Tuesday will be the 19th such gathering in Soviet history and the first since 1941. Here are highlights from some past party conferences, which under present rules can be called at any time to consider `` urgent questions of party policy.'' _ <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> held by <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> revolutionaries at an exile base in <LOCATION> Tammerfors </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, in 1905, the year of a bloody, unsuccessful uprising that set the stage for the collapse of the monarchy 12 years later and the Bolshevik Revolution that brought the Communists to power Seven party conferences were held in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and other cities outside <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> as revolutionaries plotted the overthrow of Czar Nicholas II. _ 1912, the <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> conference votes to create an all-Russian workers' newspaper, which is today the official party organ, Pravda _ 1924, a party conference held days before the death of Soviet founder <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> condemned <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Trotsky </PERSON> and his followers, signaling the rise of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, who was to lead the Soviet state for most of the next three decades _ 1929, the <ORGANIZATION> 16th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> approves the first five-year plan, the keystone of what has become a cumbersome, centrally managed economy The 16th conference also ordered a purge of party ranks that presaged <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s mass political repression of the late 1930s. _ 1941, the 18th Party Conference orders party organizations to oversee the management of industry and transport as the nation rushes to prepare for war with <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> The party's entanglement in practically all governmental and economic affairs, which grew from the resolutions of the 16th and 18th conferences, is a key target of Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s decentralization drive.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1400EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Conference-Issues Adv26   06-23 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Conference-Issues, Adv 26,0439</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With Party Conference,b0639-b0640</HEAD>
<HEAD>Major Issues of Communist Party Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No specific agenda has been announced for the 19th Communist Party Conference, but delegates may consider a wide range issues put before them by the policy-making Central Committee or by speakers recognized by the conference leadership. Whether specific recommendations emerge from the debate could provide an indication of whether <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> party leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> or more conservative forces among the delegates control the conference. The conference starts Tuesday and is now expected to last at least four days. Among the matters likely to be raised: THE PARTY'S ROLE _ <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said he wants to get party workers out of the hair of state and industry managers. The party, he said, should focus on political and ideological work, rather than try to rule every aspect of Soviet life. STALINISM _ The conference will play a role in the effort to come to terms with the legacy of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, who ran the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> with an iron hand for nearly 30 years. Part of that legacy has been a cult of personality, now condemned. He also developed the `` command'' economcy, with all decisions made in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> and passed down to individual factories and farms. PARTY CONTROL _ <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reform-minded followers may press for new rules to limit party officials to two five-year terms and could set a mandatory retirement age, perhaps 75. The move would shake up the entrenched party bureaucracy that is seen as an obstacle to reform and enable <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to bring in new blood to help press his modernization program known as `` perestroika,'' or restructuring. Expansion of multi-candidate elections, conducted by secret ballot, to all party offices up to the 300-plus members of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is another proposal. OFFICIAL POWERS _ An overhaul of the legal system to protect individual rights and insulate the system from political pressure is among the topics up for discussion. There also are proposals for some form of separation of powers, making the Supreme Soviet, now largely a rubber-stamp parliament that follows the will of the party, an independent, representative legislature. ECONOMY _ Under increasing pressure to show some tangible results of `` perestroika,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> could ask the conference to recommend changes in economic policy, particularly in agriculture, where Soviet officials say permitting families to lease farms from their collectives could produce a dramatic increase in the nation's food supply, a constant subject of consumer complaints
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
