 Joaquin </LOCATION>, which has franchises in central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Grand Met said the companies had combined annual sales of $ 355 million in the year ended Sept. 30, 1987. <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Calloway </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> chairman and chief executive, said the Grand Met franchises will `` significantly strengthen our soft drink volumes and improve operating profits, both this year and well into the future.'' He said the acquisition will dilute <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings for 1988 by about 4 cents a share. In 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> reported net income of $ 595 million, or $ 2.26 a share, on revenue of $ 11.5 billion. The sale would mean <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in <LOCATION> Purchase </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, will own bottling operations that account for about 36 percent of its domestic soft drink volume, up from about 32.4 percent. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> was not looking to acquire independent bottling operations but became interested once the bottlers became available because they are located in `` two very important areas where we are determined to strengthen <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION>'s presence'' and in some cases border territories <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> already owns. He said such acquisitions offer `` some economies of scale.'' A spokeswoman for Grand Met, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>, said her company was approached about three months ago by someone who suggested he may be prepared to offer a certain price for the bottling operations. She refused to identify the suitor. She said the inquiry prompted the company to consider whether it wanted to sell the operations, and it subsequently notifified a limited number of potential bidders that the operations were for sale. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> offered `` a very fair price.'' Grand Metropolitan is the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a multinational company based in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>. Sales in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> exceed $ 10 billion, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> has operations in soft drinks, snack foods and restaurants.
