<FIRST>r f PM-Brazil-Debt     06-23 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Debt,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Gets $5.8 Billion Debt Refinancing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The debt restructuring <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> reached with its creditor banks after eight months of tense negotiations includes $ 5.2 billion in new loans, lower interest rates and payments aimed at bringing the nation current on its obligations. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> on Wednesday said it had closed a $ 5.8 billion accord with its creditor banks to refinance some $ 64 billion of the country's massive foreign debt. The agreement ends <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s negotiations with the committee of 14 banks representing the nation's 700 creditor banks, which now must sign the accord. `` <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> has concluded one of the best refinancing accords ever reached by a debtor nation,'' Finance Minister <PERSON> Mailson </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON> told reporters at a news conference. `` The accord is not a solution to the country's foreign debt problems but it will bring <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> closer to the international financial community and remove the obstacles to economic and social development of the country,'' he said. The accord came a year and a half after <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> stopped interest payments on the $ 64 billion in bank debt in order to conserve shrinking foreign reserves. The nation's total foreign debt of $ 121 billion is the largest in the developing world. While interest payments were a crippling $ 1 billion monthly, inflation soared to 1,000 percent annual levels, money reserves and the trade surplus dropped dramatically and unemployment skyrocketed to about 25 percent. Under the agreement, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> will make a $ 345 million payment to creditors for March interest on Friday and by the end of next month will meet a $ 1 billion to cover April and May interest, bringing it current on its obligations. But <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON> said the agreement did not `` formally revoke'' the moratorium. <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON> said that might happen in October, when all creditors are expected to have signed the accord and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> receives more than $ 4 billion. Under the agreement, which covers interest due in 1987, 1988 and the first half of 1989, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> will receive $ 5.2 billion in new money to meet interest payemtns and debt falling due over the period will be spread out over 20 years, with an eight-year grace period. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> also will receive $ 600 million in short-term credit lines toward financing exports and imports. In addition, the banks agreed to sharply reduce the interest rate they had been charging on the $ 64 billion in loans. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s spread, or the extra interest charged high-risk clients above the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interbank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Offered </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rate </ORGANIZATION>, was to be cut to 0.8125 percent from the 1.75 percent set under previous agreements Among developing nations, only <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has obtained such a low spread from creditors. One of the sticking points between <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and its creditors was linkage between new money and approval of the country's economic policies from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> has argued the fund's policies are recessionary and impinge upon the country's sovereignty According to the accord, only the $ 600 million in credit lines will be linked to meeting economic goals in an IMF-approved plan and even that decision could be appealed at a later date. `` <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is the first country to sign a medium-term accord without having to have any rigid links with the fund,'' <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON> said. According to <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobrega </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> also is allowed to pull out of the agreement if there are any `` external economic shocks that impair <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s ability to meet interest payments.'' This could apply to even a drop in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s trade surplus, this year expected to reach over $ 13 billion.
