<SECOND>PM-Gas Taxes,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Governor Calls for Increased Federal Taxes on Gasoline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON>, the new chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Compact </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, says <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should substantially increase automotive fuel taxes to curb the flow at the nation's gas pumps and reduce imports of foreign oil. `` This is widely regarded as a politically unpopular proposal,'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said in a speech prepared for the 29-state commission, meeting in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION> `` Nevertheless, it is probably the most effective way to reduce dependence on oil at the gas pumps.'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> was sworn in Wednesday as the 1988-89 commission chairman, replacing <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinner </PERSON>. The commission was established by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> 52 years ago to promote development of oil and gas reserves. In his speech, <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> warned that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must reduce its dependence on foreign oil. In 1983 the nation imported two million barrels of foreign oil a day. By May 1987 that figure had doubled to four million barrels. `` Last month we were averaging 5.5 million barrels of imports a day,'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. `` If that supply is cut off, we will be faced with an economy-crippling price spike in oil,'' he said. <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> blamed low prices for some of the problem. `` The current abundance of relatively cheap oil encourages this trend.'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> also blamed the lack of energy conservation efforts for the increasing demand. Revenue from increased federal taxes on gasoline could be used to attack both problems, he said. `` The proceeds would be used to promote research in alternative fuels _ ranging from natural gas to grain alcohol fuels _ and to promote research into other conservation programs,'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. He did not propose a specific tax hike other than to call for a `` substantial increase.'' An increase of 1 cent per gallon would yield $ 1 billion a year for the federal treasury and a 25-cent tax increase would generate $ 25 billion, he said. <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> was less enthusiastic about an import tariff on foreign oil as a means of boosting the price of domestic supplies and reducing imports. Tariff-induced prices would be artificial, he said, and could hurt the economy more than they would help reduce dependence on foreign oil.
</TEXT>
