<HEAD>Judge: Government Can't Force Pension Plans Back on LTV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While the federal <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is entitled to make employers take back terminated pension plans, it has n't proven it's case yet against <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a judge has ruled. The judge on Wednesday refused to uphold the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to force the financially ailing <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> to reassume $ 2 billion in pension obligations because a new labor contract restored previously cut benefits. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweet </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> said the agency, which insures the pensions of 30 million American workers, had not explored `` all the relevant facts'' before handing three underfunded pension plans back to <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>'s Cleveland-based steel unit, <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Since the agency's decision is not sustainable on the administrative record, the appropriate remedy is to vacate the restoration decision'' that gave back responsibility for the pensions to <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>, said Sweet. `` We're very pleased,'' said <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaden </PERSON>, an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, who called the ruling `` a complete victory.'' But Sweet concluded in his 126-page opinion that the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> might be able to make its case with additional data. The judge sent the issue back to the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> `` for further consideration'' and told both sides to arrange a conference with him on further proceedings. `` While the court recognized <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION>'s authority to restore terminated plans, it did not immediately enforce restoration of the <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> plans,'' said <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoden </PERSON>. `` Instead, the court required additional fact finding by the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> on <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to fund the plans. The <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> is pleased that the court recognized our authority to restore plans, but we are disappointed that the court required additional proceedings.'' Reading from a statement, she said the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> `` is now considering other legal steps to resolve the issues of this case and relieve the uncertainty faced by retirees.'' The Dallas-based <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>, a giant steel, aerospace and energy concern, filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Code in July 1986. The <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION>, which insures pension benefits much like the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> insures bank deposits, took over <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>'s steel industry pension plans last January after the company terminated them The plans were $ 2 billion in debt, making the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>'s largest creditor. But when a new <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> labor contract with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steelworkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> restored some benefits previously cut, the agency claimed that the company was taking unfair advantage of federal funds to cut costs and gain labor peace. <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's No. 2 steelmaker, claims that restoring the plans and their deficit will seriously hamper its ability to reorganize and emerge from bankruptcy proceedings. <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s first quarter net income rose 26 percent, according to the company, because of higher steel prices and the continuing benefits of federal bankruptcy law protection. Last September the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> shifted responsibility for the underfunded pension plans back to <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION>, claiming the corporation was abusing the pension insurance program and its actions could jeopardize the agency's already strapped nationwide pension insurance fund. But <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> claimed the move violated the automatic stay provision of the Bankruptcy Code, which bars legal action against companies in reorganization. Sweet ruled, however, that the restoration of pension plans was allowed under the law that created the <ORGANIZATION> PBGC </ORGANIZATION> and the action was not subject to the automatic stay provision.
