<HEAD>Norway Continues Oil Production Restraint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> will restrain by 7.5 percent its <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil production during the second half of 1988, the Oil and <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> announced Thursday. Ministry spokesman <PERSON> Egil </PERSON> <PERSON> Helle </PERSON> said the restrained level will mean a daily production of 90,000 barrels below full capacity. But new wells and fields will be opened during the next six months, raising <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s overall production, <PERSON> Helle </PERSON> said. The cut will apply to all offshore fields. The energy ministry said that <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s average daily production during the first half of 1988 was about 1.035 billion barrels. During the second half it is projected to reach 1.125 billion barrels. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> is not a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, but it has held back on production since February 1986 in line with <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to stabilize prices. `` The government's decision to reduce the production growth is a contribution to stabilization of oil prices,'' the ministry said.
