<HEAD>Dollar Rises; `Big Ticket' Orders Fall; Stock Market Leaps</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS New grafs 2-4, Meanwhile, the ... 4.3 percent, to
UPDATE with government revising 1988 economic growth estimate.
Picks up 2nd graf pvs, The Commerce</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's economy, fueled by an export-driven manufacturing boom, expanded at a robust 3.6 percent in the first quarter, slightly less than previously thought, the government said today. Meanwhile, the government revised upwards its estimate of economic growth in 1988, predicting an expansion of 3.5 percent. The original predictions was that the economy would grow by 2.9 percent this year. <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON>, chairman of the presidential <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` The economy is doing better than even we expected. Our rosy forecast was n't rosy enough.'' He said that contrary to some fears, the economy is not overheating, with inflation holding at 4.3 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the gross national product, the broadest measure of economic health, grew to a seasonally adjusted annual level of $ 3.915 trillion in the January-March period, a $ 34.6 billion increase from three months earlier. It was a modest downward revision of a previous estimate of GNP growth in the first quarter. Last month, the government put GNP growth at 3.9 percent, up from an initial estimate of 2.3 percent in April. Analysts were expecting the slight retreat. Government economists said the first quarter growth occurred with little pickup in inflation. A price index tied to the GNP rose at an annual rate of 1.4 percent, slightly lower than the previously estimated 1.7 percent and well below the 2.7 percent pace of the fourth quarter. In a separate report today, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said after-tax corporate profits fell 1.0 percent in the first quarter to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 144.2 billion. That was down $ 1.4 billion from the last three months of 1987 and the worst performance since the first quarter of 1987, when profits fell 3.7 percent. Today's report represents a downward revision from an estimate last month, when the department said profits after taxes eased up 0.5 percent. On Wednesday, a strong rally by the dollar and indications that inflation may not be heating up as badly as earlier feared helped spark a stock market rally that pushed Wall Street to its highest levels since the October crash. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 43.03 points to 2,152.20, eclipsing the previous post-crash high of 2,131.40 set a week earlier. Aiding the market was the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report of a 2.2 percent decline in May of orders to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factories for `` big ticket'' durable goods, the biggest drop in nine months. Economists said the decline in orders was healthy because it indicated the economy was not being overheated by too much pressure on production capacity. Stocks also were helped by a big rise by the dollar in foreign exchange, a rally that caught many traders by surprise. The dollar reached almost 129 Japanese yen in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, up more than 2 yen from Tuesday's close. Analysts said the dollar's jump may have stemmed partly from the outcome of the economic summit meeting of the seven major industrialized countries in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, and a summit communique hinting there was room for the dollar to strengthen further. `` That statement gave the market a signal to buy dollars,'' said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The decline in durable goods orders surprised economists, who had expected more than a 2 percent rise in orders. But they noted the government's survey apparently did not include several multibillion-dollar orders placed to Seattle-based <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Even though the overall May decline was the largest since August's 2.3 percent fall, analysts saw little cause to worry that the report was forecasting a significant decline in manufacturing, which has been booming as the cheaper dollar bolsters export sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods. Excluding defense goods, orders fell only 0.9 percent. Excluding airplanes, they rose 0.6 percent. The financial markets read the report as good news for inflation. Many traders and some analysts have been concerned that the export boom, coupled with steady consumer demand in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, would strain manufacturers' capacity and cause shortages and price increases.
</TEXT>
