<HEAD>GAF Confirms It Is Under Investigation; Denies Wrongdoing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with GAF statement, confirmation; no
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> confirmed Thursday that it is under investigation for possible securities law violations, but a spokesman for the company denied any wrongdoing. According to the spokesman, the focus of the investigation appears to relate to the disposition of a portion of <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION>'s stock position in <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> during late 1986. <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> made a hostile bid for Carbide in 1985 but reached a standstill agreement with the company the following year. According to unidentified sources quoted in Thursday's editions of the Wall Street Journal, the federal government is looking into <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION>'s accumulation of Carbide stock through <ORGANIZATION> Jefferies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> securities firm once headed by <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON>. Jefferies pleaded guilty to two felonies after being implicated in a stock parking scheme by convicted arbitrager <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, who is now serving time in prison. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION>'s vice chairman and chief administrative officer, has been named as having had an agreement with <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> regarding alleged stock parking and manipulation, the newspaper said. Under their alleged agreement, <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> agreed to reimburse the Jefferies firm for losses incurred in trading in Carbide stock. The Journal's sources noted that <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON> did not make any money from the scheme. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> appears undecided as to whether it will seek criminal charges in the case, the paper said. `` Both the company and its officials are innocent of any wrongdoing,'' a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> said. In early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> had fallen $ 1.62 -LCB- a share to $ 46 -LCB-. According to the Journal, <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> is the first industrial company to be targeted for investigation in the government's widespread probe of abuses within the securities industry. The paper noted that the investigation could hamper <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Heyman </PERSON>'s planned $ 1.27 billion leveraged buyout of the <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON>, N.J.-based chemicals and building materials company. But the <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said, `` the outcome of this matter will not have any material financial consequences to the company, and plans for management's proposed leveraged buyout of <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> remain unaffected.''
