<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Soar At Opening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened sharply higher today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid fears that crop damage from the scorching drought was bound to deepen. Soybeans for July delivery blasted to a 15-year high in early trading after topping $ 10.76 -LCB- a bushel, the 1977 top price for a near-month contract. Scattered rain fell in parts of the eastern Farm Belt Wednesday but analysts said only a return to normal rainfall patterns could ward off further wreckage in the country's corn, oat, spring wheat and soybean fields. Experts estimate the drought has already devastated at least 50 percent of the oat and spring wheat crops, 30 percent of corn and will begin to take a significant toll on soybeans in July. Corn for July delivery opened up the 10-cents-a bushel limit; July soybeans quickly traded up their 45-cent limit, putting the contract within -LCB- cent of $ 11 a bushel; and oat futures opened limit-up. Weekend weather forecasts for more light, scattered showers in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> may have a slight slowing effect on the rally, said <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Leow </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I would say the market is going to remain strong, although some profit-taking may come in today and tomorrow,'' she said. In early trading, wheat was 7 cents to 11 cents higher with July at $ 3.92 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 4 cents to 10 cents higher with July at $ 3.54 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 14 -RCB- cents to 15 cents higher with July at a record $ 3.48 a bushel; soybeans were 21 cents to 45 cents higher with July at $ 10.99 -LCB- a bushel. Livestock and meat futures were sharply lower to limit-down in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .42 cent to 1.20 cents lower with August at 62.12 a pound; feeder cattle were 1.15 cents to the limit 1.50 cents lower with August at 69.15 cents a pound; hogs were the limit 1.50 cents lower to .05 cent higher with July at 44.40 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .10 cent to the limit 2 cents lower with July at 40 cents a pound. Livestock and meat futures closed sharply lower Wednesday.
