<HEAD>Battle Over Societe Generale To End</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Italian financier <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> has agreed to sharply reduce his stake in <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belgique </ORGANIZATION>, ending a lengthy takeover battle for <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>'s largest holding company, sources said Thursday. Under terms of a settlement, <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> will sell part of his 45 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Cie. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financiere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION>, a French banking company that, along with its allies, holds a slim majority. The sale will reduce <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON>'s holdings to about 15 percent, thereby blocking his ability to manipulate decisions that require a 75 percent vote of shareholders. In return, however, <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> would get a cash payment, at least three seats on <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>'s board and would increase his stake in <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION>, according to sources who spoke on condition of anonymity. The agreement is expected to be formally announced Friday at a news conference called by <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>, whose holdings in industries including energy, finance, chemicals, mining and transport control about a third of <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>'s economy. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> announced in January he sought to control <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>. The Belgian company resisted his overtures but had to look for foreign support in <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION>, which along with the Belgian insurer <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> came to control slightly more than 50 percent of the holdign company's shares. At a special meeting two months ago, shareholders spurned <ORGANIZATION> De </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benedetti </ORGANIZATION>'s bid to win board seats for himself and two allies. <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION>'s strengthened stake under the settlement should allow the French group to run <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> with its own new chief executive, reorganizing the company's often criticized strategy as well as its management structure. A statement issued earlier this week confirming negotiations were underway said <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> and its allies will back the nomination of <PERSON> Herve </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmoy </PERSON>, a French banker, to <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>'s board, while <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> and his allies will abstain. It is expected that <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmoy </PERSON> will be asked to take over a large part of <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>'s management. The French-Belgian group was also reported to be interested in looking for more foreign partners, including the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> media magnate <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>. Under the agreement between <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION>, Belgians' stake in <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> will decline substantially, according to Belgian press reports The conservative daily <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Libre </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belgique </ORGANIZATION> wrote: `` The decision center has moved to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. Belgians will have to fight hard to defend the national character of the company.''
