<SECOND>PM-FCC-Indecency, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0078,0649</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs, The Kansas, with comment
from station's attorney; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> today voted to levy the first fine for violation of its new decency standards on a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> television station that aired a sexy movie during prime time. Commissioners voted 2-1 to impose the maximum $ 2,000 fine against KZKC-TV for its May 1987 broadcast of `` Private Lessons,'' which included scenes of a bare-breasted woman seducing a teen-ager. The <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> station aired the movie at 8 p.m., a time the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> has determined children are likely to be in the audience. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s guidelines allow `` indecent'' material to be aired after midnight to lessen the risk that such programs could be viewed by children. Attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, who represents the station, said he was `` shocked and surprised and outraged by the imposition of the maximum fine in light of the circumstances.'' He said the sanction is unfair because `` we do n't know what is indecent because the statute does n't provide any guidance.'' All three commissioners said that the movie fit the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s definition of indecency, but Commissioner <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> disagreed with the fine She said `` parents, not the commission, should bear the primary responsibility of deciding what their children should watch at night.'' <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> disagreed, saying the government must help parents in deciding what their children watch on television. He said it is reasonable to assume that there are unsupervised children in the audience during prime-time hours. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said Wednesday that the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s record on indecency has been clear. `` While respecting the First Amendment rights of all citizens, we have taken clear and decisive action to enforce the statutory ban on broadcast obscenity and to further restrict the broadcast of indecent material so as to put parents in a better position to control their children's access to this type of material,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns <ORGANIZATION> KZKC </ORGANIZATION>, has said the film had been cut by an inexperienced editor and violated company standards, but a fine would be inappropriate because the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s indecency guidelines are ambiguous and are being applied to TV for the first time. The movie, the owners said, was aired little more than a month after the new standards were adopted. The FCC guidelines are being challenged in court by broadcasting groups, news organizations and public interest advocates as being unconstitutionally vague and overbroad. Media Central acknowledged that the airing of the 1980 sex comedy violated <ORGANIZATION> KZKC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` broadcast standards and sense of good taste,'' but the company said station officials took immediate corrective action after the broadcast, including a clarification of the station's policy on frontal nudity. Attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, representing <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION>, said it would be premature to comment before the commission acted. Media Central, based in <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, is awaiting court action on a reorganization plan it filed under Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Act. `` Private Lessons'' is about a wealthy 15-year-old boy who is seduced by his housekeeper. The film includes several scenes in which the housekeeper is shown bare-breasted. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> decided in April 1987 to apply the wording of a 1978 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision that said indecent material is `` language or material that depicts or describes, in terms patently offensive as measured by contemporary community standards for the broadcast medium, sexual or excretory activities or organs.'' The commission said indecent material may be aired only when there is a reasonable risk that children are not in the audience. In a subsequent ruling in November 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> said it would consider that children were not likely to be in the audience after midnight. Previously the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> had considered 10 p.m. the cutoff time.
</TEXT>
