<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A top <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> official whose phone was tapped in the massive Pentagon bribery probe has begun cooperating with prosecutors, while a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said today that others are following suit. Deputy Assistant <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaines </PERSON>, whose office was searched last week, has begun telling prosecutors what he knows, sources familiar with the investigation said. One <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said today that `` there has been some interest shown on the part of some individuals in cooperating with the investigation.'' He said that some information `` has already been obtained.'' Other sources familiar with the probe said the interest was coming from subjects who are working in the Pentagon. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told reporters he has arranged for a report on the present status of the investigation, but did not say how soon he expects to receive it. Responding to a question as he posed for pictures with visiting Australian Prime Minister <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> today, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` I am asking, and have arranged - they are coming over to give me a full report.'' He said the report would deal with the question of `` where are we now and how much do we know already?'' The <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported today that investigators believe <PERSON> Gaines </PERSON> was a principal supplier of Pentagon documents to defense consultant <PERSON> Melvyn </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>, who was assistant secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </O