<HEAD>American Homes Are Filled With Consumer Electronics, Survey Shows</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer electronics are n't just for yuppies, an industry group said Thursday in releasing a Gallup survey that found nearly two-thirds of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> homes owned a videocassette recorder. Ownership of VCRs has mushroomed to 65 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> households, said the <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which sponsored the nationwide telephone survey of 1,008 adults this spring. Televisions, which topped the popularity list, were owned by 99 percent of the households surveyed. Among other items included in the survey, telephone answering machines were in 24 percent of the homes, personal computers in 18 percent and compact disk players in 14 percent. Some people even claimed to have facsimile machines at home _ about 1 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> Gallup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> survey found. `` Our products are not luxuries owned by a privileged, select few,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Friel </PERSON>, vice president of the trade organization's <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said in a news conference Not surprisingly, the survey found the households with the highest incomes had the most consumer electronics products. But it was n't just rich singles. Ownership was higher among families with children. For example, about 78 percent of families with children had VCRs, while only 40 percent of single-member households did. In general, ownership of consumer electronics products was higher in the East and West than in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> or South. For example, telephone answering machines were in 36 percent of households in the West and 27 percent in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. They were in 19 percent of the households in the South and 17 percent of those in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, the survey found. On televisions, the survey found that 31 percent of households owned one, 33 percent owned two and 35 percent owned three or more. Forty-three percent of households with children own three or more televisions. Questions asked of the whole group have a margin of error of 4 percentage points, while questions asked of subgroups have higher error margins, a Gallup spokesman said. Since it was a survey done by phone, the results are valid only for homes with telephones _ people without phones would tend to own less consumer electronics equipment.
</TEXT>
