<FIRST>r f AM-Europe-Aviation     06-23 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-Aviation,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Discuss Future Of European Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KERKRADE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Common Market leaders should remove obstacles to airline mergers by carriers based in different member nations, Western European aviation experts said Thursday at a seminar here. `` Far-reaching liberalization of the airline industry is essential to ensure a free flow of goods and services within the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Raben </PERSON>, head of the Dutch civil aviation agency, told a news conference. `` And it is crystal-clear that obstacles against international mergers must be removed.'' He spoke at the end of the day-long seminar in this southern Dutch town on the future of the airline industry in the deregulated, liberalized Common Market envisioned after 1992. The conference, convened by <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON> Neelie </PERSON> <PERSON> Smit-Kroes </PERSON>, drew 40 representatives from Common Market airlines, civil aviation authorities and governments. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> has a 1992 goal of removing all trade barriers among its members, including <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s patchwork of bilateral aviation agreements Although some nations, notably <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, already have liberalized aviation agreements, most European countries severely limit the freedom of operation for foreign airlines. After 1992, European airlines would be free to choose their destinations and flight frequencies. Experts at the seminar predicted that only a few very large carriers will be able to survive. Seminar participants heard a report by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Passenger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associations </ORGANIZATION> on possible effects of European airline mergers on the flying public. The <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> commissioned the report by the private, Geneva-based organization. In the report, <ORGANIZATION> IFAPA </ORGANIZATION>'s executive director <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Lipman </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> members should maintain some regulations to safeguard airline passengers. He said that after the 1978 deregulation of civil aviation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, passenger complaints on congestion, delays and bad service mushroomed. <PERSON> Raben </PERSON> said that while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government abolished many of the regulations affecting the airline industry in one move, `` we're planning a gradual change in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
