<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Analysis Bjt   06-23 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Analysis, Bjt,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar's Latest Jump Is Another Quirk In Unpredictable Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world's sudden enthusiasm for the dollar is built on the vicissitudes of guesswork and opinion, and it may not last. After months of stability, the dollar has jumped about 3 percent against the Japanese yen and 4 percent against the West German mark since June 10. Investors who used to treat the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency as a sick patient are speculating about how high it might rise. Many analysts are happy to explain why they believe the dollar's rise is long overdue and well-justified, but watertight explanations have proven notoriously leaky in the past Certainly there have been some reasonable theories for the increase in the dollar's value. For example: _ A sharp improvement in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> merchandise trade deficit for the month of April raised hopes that the nation was on a steady path to balanced trade _ <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> reported extremely strong economic growth in early 1988, raising the possibility that Japanese inflation would increase and undermine the value of the yen In another potential inflation signal, the Japanese and West German money supplies have been growing rapidly. _ The finance leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> industrialized nations left open the possibility that they would tolerate a further increase in the dollar's value But those explanations -LRB- and others -RRB- notwithstanding, the latest dollar rise is more of a quirk than a response to fundamentals. The truth is that no one is certain what the dollar's `` natural'' value is _ if there is even such a thing After all, history shows the dollar can swing a long way from equilibrium. In early 1985 the dollar was worth twice what it is worth now in terms of yen and marks. In light of that experience, who can say for sure it is properly valued now? Although the latest pressure on the dollar has been upward, one group of economists says it should fall another 15 or 20 percent. Psychology _ the mass psychology of the markets _ is the real reason for the dollar's latest move. Traders who make a living by trading currencies were bored and frustrated by the months of stability in the dollar. Some of them undoubtedly made profits by engineering a rally in the dollar. The dollar's strength is new and it could be short-lived. As recently as the first quarter of this year, private investors were so chary of the dollar that foreign central banks were forced to finance more than 60 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> current account deficit. Foreign official assets in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> rose $ 25 billion in the three-month period, more than in any quarter of 1987, notes <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>, senior economist of <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Sometime around April, Ms. <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> said, `` There was a massive change in psychology.'' Suddenly, she said, private foreign investors decided they were n't afraid to hold dollars. `` It's one of the virtuous-circle kind of things. The dollar has remained stable, so people think the dollar will continue to remain stable. It just keeps feeding on itself.'' Virtuous circles can quickly change to vicious circles. `` As long as you are dependent on foreign capital inflows, the dollar is extremely vulnerable,'' noted <PERSON> Jai </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bajaj </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Yes, he said, it is possible that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will move surely and steadily from trade deficit to trade surplus by sometime in 1990. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the next administration may make steady progress on reducing the federal budget deficit. But then again, ill-timed moves in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> or a sudden deterioration in the trade account could inspire a run on the dollar, <ORGANIZATION> Bajaj </ORGANIZATION> said. `` You can very easily fracture foreign confidence in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic management,'' he said. `` I see lots of slippages. Lots of danger.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE: <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Coy </PERSON> covers trade and technology for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
