<HEAD>Money Supply Measures Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 All three measures of the nation's money supply tumbled in mid-June, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> said its narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, fell $ 2.1 billion in the week ended June 13 to a seasonally adjusted $ 771.8 billion from $ 773.9 billion the previous week. It said the measure known as M2 fell $ 4.8 billion to a seasonally adjusted $ 3,013 billion from $ 3,018 billion. An even broader measure, M3, fell $ 1.8 billion to a seasonally adjusted $ 3,794 billion from $ 3,796 billion. M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations of $ 100,000. The central bank considers the two broader measures of the money supply as well as the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the difference between short - and long-term interest rates in setting its monetary policy But most economists say that recent movements in the money supply do not appear to have played a very significant role in those deliberations. In other reports Thursday: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> reported commercial and industrial loans at major <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> banks rose $ 952 million in the week ended June 15, compared with a gain of $ 133 million the previous week _ The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said discount window borrowings, excluding extended credit, averaged $ 498 million a day in the week ended Wednesday, down from $ 562 million the previous week _ The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> reported that the monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation, was $ 278.2 billion in the two-week period ended Wednesday, up from $ 276.1 billion two weeks earlier
</TEXT>
