<HEAD>Mexican Market Reels After Shakeup</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Update planned with Thursday's close</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s stock market reeled Thursday after a shake-up at the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the director, the operations chief and billions of missing pesos had to be replaced. Exchange officials said Wednesday they had accepted the resignations of Director-General <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Segura </PERSON> <PERSON> Quiroz </PERSON> and Operations Director <PERSON> Reynaldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Balsaldua </PERSON>, who has been in a coma since attempting suicide last month. <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunez </PERSON>, who was once vice president of the exchange's regulatory agency, was named interim director-general Officials also said they were revamping the exchange's controls, finances, administration and operations. The volatile market promptly nose-dived, closing down 10,968.95 points, about 5.45 percent. `` It's a big drop. There's no question,'' said <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Heyman </PERSON>, author of a Mexican best-seller on investing and head of investment strategy at a leading brokerage house here. Some analysts blamed the stock exchange's fall, at least in part, on the scandal, saying it had shaken investor confidence. Others called it an expected correction. `` There's never just one reason for things to happen,'' <PERSON> Heyman </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` The market has risen rather sharply since mid-May, from 144,000 to 203,000 _ about 33 percent. We expected a correction.'' The reorganization came after an audit revealed the exchange was missing at least 15.7 billion pesos of its own _ not investors' _ money, or about $ 7 million. It is still not clear whether the money vanished through fraud, mismanagement or a combination of the two. Exchange officials say the shortage could reach 20 billion pesos or more. Exchange President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Harp </PERSON> <PERSON> Helu </PERSON> said Wednesday that the condition of the operations director, in a coma since shooting himself on May 13 at the exchange, has `` blocked a precise understanding of'' what happened to the money. Last year, the Mexican market was one of the world's hottest. But it fell 74 percent in 28 trading days following the worldwide stock crash in mid-October. Officials have been struggling to restore confidence in the market and minimize the growing scandal. In addition to the reorganization, members of the exchange replaced the missing money and agreed to a code of ethics. Some critics have complained about the exchange's failure to turn the case over to judicial authorities for a criminal investigation.
