<HEAD>Judge Finds No Evidence Union Staged Boycott</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge said Thursday he found no evidence the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Attendants </ORGANIZATION> instigated a massive overtime boycott at <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>, which was forced to cancel 179 flights over the Memorial Day holiday. Although <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Standish </PERSON> said the refusal of many flight attendants to work overtime during the three-day weekend was `` part of a concerted refusal to fly,'' he said evidence was insufficient to prove the union ordered or encouraged such a job action. The judge stopped short, however, of denying <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>'s request for a preliminary injunction barring future overtime boycotts. He said he would issue a ruling on the airline's request Friday. Although neither side would claim victory or defeat, flight attendants union attorney <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenfield </PERSON> said, `` Clearly he -LRB- Standish -RRB- has n't found any proof of union involvement so far.'' <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> declined to comment on the judge's actions until a ruling is issued He said the airline has no plans to change its long-standing tradition of scheduling overtime for its flight attendants. About 11,000 passengers were affected when hundreds of flight attendants refused to work overtime during Memorial Day. The airline said it lost an estimated $ 1.1 million. <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> officials testified during the two-day hearing that about one-third of the airline's flight attendants routinely work more than the 85 hours a month mandated by their contract. Under their two-year pact, which expires in August, <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>'s 3,000 flight attendants can choose to work up to, but no more than, 95 hours a month <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> sued the union last week amid stalled contract negotiations with the 1,000 flight attendants of <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which merged with <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> in April. Flight attendants union spokeswoman <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> <PERSON> Maki </PERSON> said major unresolved issues in the negotiations, which began in July and currently are being mediated, include an airline proposal to pay <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' former attendants at a different rate than <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>'s. <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> has a two-tiered pay system for its flight attendants, and the proposal for <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> workers would create two additional tiers until parity is attained in three years, she said. If <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> could have proved union involvement in the Memorial Day job action, the flight attendants union could have been in violation of the federal Railway Labor Act, which prohibits organized work slowdowns, strikes, sickouts and other such actions during contract negotiations. On Thursday, Ms. <PERSON> Maki </PERSON> testified she told attendants at union meetings and in written memos in May that extra flying time was voluntary but did not try to discourage members from working overtime. `` We told them we will not sponsor anything like that,'' she said. But <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Reinert </PERSON> said impromptu notices posted in crew lounges encouraging an overtime boycott and statements Ms. <PERSON> Maki </PERSON> made to the press expressing her delight over the job action were evidence of union involvement.
