<HEAD>Kickoff of Big Antitrust Suit Against Insurance Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tough-talking federal judge on Thursday kicked off pre-trial sessions of a massive, 18-state antitrust lawsuit against some of the nation's major insurance companies, accused of a conspiracy to cut liability coverage for government and business. Reporters were told there could be as many as 15 more plaintiffs _ presently unnamed companies from around the country _ before the complex case goes to trial years from now. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, leading the plaintiffs, said after the two-hour session that he would `` be happy'' if the trial could begin three years from now. The states are asking for unspecified damages and an injunction to prevent the insurers from repeating alleged violations. A major contributor to the insurance crisis was `` an illegal boycott,'' because the companies pressured the <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, a 1,400-member industry trade group, to quit distributing standard forms to make it difficult for individual companies to continue offering certain liability coverage. There will be no emotional, jury-type pleadings, only the facts, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarzer </PERSON> warned a huge ceremonial courtroom of more than 100 lawyers representing the plaintiffs and 32 insurance companies, underwriting agencies and brokers. `` There will be no duplicate arguments,'' the judge sternly ordered. The opening session was the lawsuit's status conference, roughly the judge's procedural `` road map'' aimed at narrowing the issues, setting rules and limits for discovery, and naming motion, argument and hearing dates leading to trial. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Guido </PERSON> <PERSON> Severi </PERSON> said he anticipated that 14 or 15 more plaintiffs would be joining the action. He said a multi-district panel would decide how the new complaints would be heard. <PERSON> Schwarzer </PERSON>, referring to himself as a `` resource'' of the case forced to limit the volume of documents laid before him, strenuously resisted efforts to convince him to handle defendants on an individual basis. Some defense lawyers estimated that the plaintiffs' two years of investigation had produced 100,000 pages and that the companies were entitled to see them as part of discovery. The judge said he was n't so sure of that. The judge limited to 25 pages pleadings pertaining to the law, principally the McCarran-Ferguson Act, that says insurance companies ca n't be sued for antitrust violations unless conspiracy is involved. The plaintiff states are <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> filed a similar suit in its own state court. Regarding discovery _ information either side is entitled to learn about the other's case _ the judge said he would take `` a dim view'' of efforts aimed at `` broad exploratory'' disclosures. `` Discovery is limited to issues that are essential to deal with the issues on both sides,'' ruled <PERSON> Schwarzer </PERSON>, one of the nation's most respected jurists on management of issues of disclosure The judge ordered a limit of six months for discovery, all motions to be filed by Dec. 16, state responses on April 18, 1989; arguments June 16, 1989, and a hearing July 7, 1989. The leading defendants are <ORGANIZATION> Hartford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Aetna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Cigna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. They are accused of arranging among themselves, starting around 1984, to make liability insurance unavailable or prohibitively expensive. `` Anti-consumer revisions were made in the -LRB- forms -RRB- as a result of boycotts, threats, intimidation and other coercive conduct by the defendants,'' said the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> complaint by state Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON>.
